deck_description: Evol Deck 2024

deck_excerpt: EMERGENCY! and Rescue-Ace Preventer are finally out in Masterduel! Combined with Snake-Eye, this fire deck is nigh unstoppable!
deck_description:
Thanks to the selection pack "Nightmare Arrivals," EMERGENCY! and Rescue-Ace Preventer have (finally) made their appearance in Masterduel! Combined with Snake-Eye, this fire deck is nigh unstoppable. If you want to reach high levels on Masterduel ladder with a reliable deck that can either 1st or 2nd and can cram a ton of staples while being consistently powerful, Rescue-ACE is a good deck to play!
 
All fire decks that feature a level 1 fire starter has recieved an unbelievable power boost with the release of the "Snake-Eyes" cards from the "Ride Into the Future" pack in Masterduel! Not only is there enhanced consistency with the Snake-Eye and Diabellestar cards, the power ceiling of RESCUE-ACE has dramatically increased as well, since the new additions to the deck allow it to link spam like no tomorrow! Powerful link bosses like Heatsoul, Amblowhale and Promethean Princess are easily made with a singular Snake-Eyes Ash, on top of your Turbulence's 4 set backrow!
 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
This deck features two sets of cards in it, RESCUE-ACE and Snake-Eye. A reduced RESCUE-ACE core is included because of the consistency boost the Snake-Eye cards give, and now they number 16 cards. 2 hydrant rather than 3 is used since the card can now be seached/summoned from deck with the Snake-Eye cards. 3 EMERGENCY! are included since they function as "emergency teleport" and are effectively 1-card playstarters. 4 Rescue-ACE spells/traps are included as targets for Turbulence to set from deck. REINFORCE! isn't included since the card seems fairly inconsequential compared to the other quick-play spells and traps. One for One is included since it's an additional copy of any level 1 fire you need summoned from deck. 
 
Thanks to the consistency boost from Snake-Eyes and Bonfire, a whopping 15 STAPLES is included in the strategy, including 14 handtraps (RESCUE-ACE Impulse is actually a handtrap!). This means you're always going to interrupt your opponent, no matter what turn it is! The usual "Maxx C" package is included so the pilot can win the Maxx C minigame.
 
Unlike earlier iterations of this deck, the Extra Deck is now used a lot since the Snake-Eye cards grant this deck immense link climb ability. Linkuriboh + Sunlight Wolf summon Heatsoul, I:P Masquera can be summoned from the backrow during your opponent's turn with Flamberge Dragon, etc. The Extra Deck is a toolbox for answers to specific game states. Since many monsters in the Extra Deck aren't required, they can be banish fodder for Pot of Prosperity. 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
Rescue-ACE functions as a control-centred midrange deck. Usually, the deck summons Turbulence, sets 4 spells/traps from the deck (two interruptions and two follow-up cards). Combined with the Snake-Eyes cards, this strategy has become much more aggressive since it is able to link climb quickly to Accesscode for an OTK. The hand also may have Rescue-ACE warriors that function as handtraps to net further advantage from deck, hand or GY. 
 
Here is the deck's main combo: 
 
Snake-Eyes Ash + Rescue-ACE Turbulence/Extender = 4 set Rescue-ACE spells/traps (interruption and follow-up) + Promethean Princess in GY (monster destruction) + Amblowhale (link-monster summon and 1 card destruction) + Heatsoul (draw 2) + follow-up for next turn in hand
  1. Normal summon Snake-Eye Ash. Search for Poplar from deck with Ash' effect.
  2. Activate Poplar's trigger effect in hand to special summon it to the field.
  3. Activate Poplar's trigger effect to search for Original Sinful Spoils - Snake-Eyes.
  4. Link away Poplar for Linkuriboh. Activate Poplar's trigger effect to place it in the backrow.
  5. Activate Snake-Eye Ash's effect to send itself and Poplar to the GY to summon from deck Flamberge Dragon.
  6. Activate Flamberge Dragon's effect to place Poplar in the backrow.
  7. Activate Original Sinful Spoils - Snake-Eyes sending Poplar to summon from deck RESCUE-ACE Hydrant. 
  8. Activate Hydrant's effect to search for a RESCUE-ACE Turbulence or extender from deck (either Attacker or Fire Engine). 
  9. Link away Hydrant  + Flamberge Dragon to link summon Salamangreat Sunlight Wolf.
  10. Flamberge Dragon's trigger effect activates to summon Poplar + Hydrant from the GY.
  11. Activate RESCUE-ACE extender's effect in the hand to summon itself. 
  12. Link away Hydrant + RESCUE-ACE extender + Linkuriboh to link summon Promethean Princess to the zone above Sunlight Wolf. 
  13. Sunlight Wolf's trigger effect recovers you any fire monster in the GY (You can recover Ash Blossom for example!)
  14. Activate Turbulence's effect to summon itself from the hand banishing in GY Hydrant + RESCUE-ACE extender.
  15. Activate Turbulence's effect to set 4 RESCUE-ACE spells/traps from deck. Typically, you'd set ALERT! (search), RESCUE! (monster reborn), EXTINGUISH! (destroy monster) and CONTAIN! (monster negate).
  16. Activate Promethean Princess' effect to summon any fire monster from the GY. Link away the summoned fire monster + Promethean Princess to link summon Amblowhale.
  17. Activate Linkuriboh's effect to summon itself from the GY by tributing Poplar. 
  18. Link away Linkuriboh + Sunlight Wolf to link summon Heatsoul. Activate Heatsoul's effect to draw 1 card.
Rescue Ace may not have much negates, but the plethora of interruptions and the sheer advantage accrued by the deck wins many games. Next turn, you'll have so many cards in hand and follow-up in GY/field that you'll almost certainly OTK!
 
There are plenty of combos that fit particular situations, but the combo featured above is the mose optimal. Due to the number of starters it has, it can certainly play through handtraps/interruption, and if one strategy gets stopped, it can pivot to the other!
 
GENERAL TIPS
  • Snake-Eye Ash is the card you really want to resolve. Try to bait out your opponent's interruptions before you play this card.
  • If either a dark or fire is in the GY opponent's GY, (think Bystials or Ash Blossom), this deck can easily summon Dharc/Hiita so then they can link climb up to Promethean Princess!
  • Promethean Fire Princess may lock you into fire, but that's only when it's on the field! When you link her away for Amblowhale or another fire card, that's when you're free summon other monster attributes. 
  • Hydrant/Ash/Poplar can be linked away into Relinquished Anima! Opponents surprisingly leave many monsters vulnerable in the zones in front of the Extra Monster Zones, so when you have used Hydrant's effect to search, you may as well use it as a boardbreaker!
  • Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
The Rescue-ACE variant is quite possibly the best version of Snake-Eyes right now because of EMERGECY! consistency boost and Preventer's interruption/extension. Rescue-ACE Snake-Eye is my recommendation for your next ladder climb up the leagues Masterduel since it is consistent, can go 1st and 2nd, can play nicely into Maxx "C" and more!
 
GLHF Duelists!

The Chant of the Voice

This deck revolves around the powerful "Voiceless Voice" archetype, utilizing Light and Dark attributes to dominate the duel.

Core Strategy:

  • Ritual Focus: Multiple copies of "Pre-Preparation of Rites" and "Saffira, Queen of Dragons" enable consistent access to strong Fusion monsters like "Saffira, Dragon Queen of the Voiceless Voice" and "Sauravis, the Ancient and Ascended."
  • Hand Disruption & Protection: Hand traps like "Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring," "Effect Veiler," and "Infinite Impermanence" disrupt your opponent's plays, while "Called by the Grave" and "Crossout Designator" target specific threats.
  • Resource Management: "Pot of Prosperity" fuels your hand, while "Prayers of the Voiceless Voice" searches for archetype cards.

Key Cards:

  • Saffira Package: The core of the deck, with "Saffira, Dragon Queen of the Voiceless Voice" offering high attack and negation, while "Sauravis, Dragon Sage of the Voiceless Voice" provides search and recursion.
  • Light Bringer Lucifer & Gyakutenno Megami: These powerful Light and Dark monsters enable Fusion Summons and offer additional effects.
  • Wingweaver: A versatile monster that can negate Spells/Traps or search for Ritual cards like "Advanced Ritual Art."

Extra Deck:

The Extra Deck offers a toolbox of powerful Fusion monsters like "Saffira, Dragon Deity of the Voiceless Voice" and "Herald of the Arc Light" for various situations. Knightmare monsters provide removal options, while "Accesscode Talker" delivers high piercing damage.

Overall, this deck offers a powerful and consistent strategy with a focus on Fusion Summons and hand disruption. It utilizes the "Voiceless Voice" archetype's strong effects to control the field and overpower the opponent.

deck_excerpt: Competitive, Budget, Learning Curve, Midrange Deck.
deck_description:
Yup 7 URs and even with all the staples I've crafted these are still the boss monsters I go into, Simple things you need to know this deck is not Explosive or Too Slow its midrange no matter if go first or second you have plays to make.

Never be afraid to pop your cards you will get them back via Combo & Avarice. Outlast your opponent. 

Going down the list the Engine is only 21 cards the rest can be subbed out at you're leisure for cards like Maxx-C & Called By / Ash 

First the Engine 

Zoodiac Ratpier x1 , Zoodiac Bunnyblast x1 , Zoodiac Ramram x1 , Zoodiac Thoroughblade 3x , Zoodiac Whiptail x3. 

Fire Formation Tenki 3x , Zoodiac Barrage 3x , Zoodiac Combo x2 , Pot of Avarice x 3 , Foolish Burial Goods x1. 

Zoodiac Drident 1x , Zoodiac Tigermortar x 3 , Zoodiac Chakanine x3 , Zoodiac Boarbow 2x , Zoodiac Hammerkong 2x , Divine Arsenal AA Zeus 1x, Utopic Future 1x , Utopic Draco Future x1 , Infinitrack Fortress Megaclops 1x. 

___ 

 

Now for the Combo's , Key Terms | NS = Normal Summon , SS = Special Summon | Stack = SS Over said card | Pop : Destroy ( Target ) 

 ( Linear ) NS Any Zoo , Stack Boarbow , Stack Hammerkong , Stack Drident set whatever you have pass is your safest play against Nib. 

 ( Steps )

Step 1. Zoodiac Barrage Pop any NS Zoo , SS Ramram from deck. ( NS Thoroughblade & Discard Ramram works as well ) 

Step 2. Stack Chakanine onto Ramram, Use Chak to detach Ramram, SS Ramram. 

Step 3. Stack Drident onto Chak then detatch to Pop Ramram, Activate Ramram SS Chak 

Step 4. Stack Tigermortar onto Drident detatch then target Chak choose drident

Step 5. Use Chak and SS drident. 

Step 6. Use all 3 xyz Make Megaclops  or  Make Utopic Future over Tiger & Chak, Then Make Draco Future over Utopic ( only if you have Whiptail in hand to attatch to Drident )  

The most Important Notes : Zoodiac Boarbow can attack directly, Its your Easiest way to access Zeus, Zeus : He can detach 2 materials Send everything on field to graveyard you can make this guy have up to 6 Materials !

 

There's more stuff but you'll learn as you play, Good Luck on ladder.

Don't Forget to Craft :  Maxx "C" x 3 , Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring x3 , Called by The Grave x2. Buy the 750 Bundles in Store & Solo Mode for F2p Gems.

fun deck

This deck is a go second deck with a lot of tool box cards. Magical Musketeer has been a tier 3 and lower deck due to the sheer amount of power creep in the last decade. Its only strength is the spell/trap handtraps that interact with the opponent by negating cards, destroying face up cards, and banishing cards from grave. Its best matchup in the current format is stun since you can pick off fossil dyna more consistently than they can open judgment. (A testament of how slow a deck needs to be in order for the deck to dominate).

The Fiendsmith support provides the consistency that Musketeer has longed for because you can now search Caspar, Starfire or whatever Musketeer you need. Basically, you are now running 9 copies of Caspar/Starfire and 7 copies of Doc, Calamity, Wild and Kidbrave without taking up the deck space. You could run a similar Small World Package consisting of Ash, Effect Veiler and Nibiru as Small World bridges, but you always had to a) draw no Musketeers and b) needed one of the aforementioned drawn with Small World for the package to be worth it. Fiendsmith works as both a way to get to Starfire/Caspar and as a way to proc them. Its just an efficient searcher for Musketeers. Also, fi you are set on Musketeers, Lurrie is searched and dumped to become the second body needed to make Sequentia. 

The Fiendsmith combo lets your go first endboard be more than Caspar + Starfire pass, converting into Apollousa or High King Caesar with a Musketeer on board that can't be targeted. Prior to Fiendsmith, if you didn't open Caspar or Starfire going first, you were in a bad spot. Going second, if Max got negated, you just passed, now you can convert it into Fiendsmith stuff, making cards like Ash only stop the Musketeer side of the deck, requiring 2 negations minimum to stop the entire combo. Overall, the Fiendsmith engine is a welcome addition and should be run moving forward in every Musketeer deck.  

As for the the power cards of the deck, Super Poly, Link into the Vrains, and Ultimate Slayer all have the clause: your opponent cannot respond, making them 'guaranteed' against most meta decks. The idea is to ensure your Muskets can hit the field and these cards generate advantage through denying negation. Super Poly eats a minimum of 2 cards, Ultimate slayer does the same without the discard, and Link into the Vrains guarantees Max resolving his mass search effect or summon effect. If any of light fiend links get destroyed, it recurs 1 light fiend from grave (per copy of LITV). Also, it serves as an extender, so if you get Nibbed, you can just normal summon to continue your plays. 

Extra deck is running the bare minimum to do Musketeer and Fiendsmith combos because it works with the assumption you will just be shuffling everything back. If people start playing D.D. Crow in a format, bump ratios to 2 so you won't get stifled by a banished Lacrimosa or something. (That also means Super Poly or Ultimate Slayer will have to cut their engine size). Ultimate slayer runs the best of each summon type, allowing you to pop with N'tss, bounce with Malong, and negate with Aggregator. Garura is there because of the Super Poly Engine, but you can always just draw a card against fusion decks.   

Side deck can be tailered to the event you are going to, so this is by no means fixed. Run more s/t removal if your locals is all stun, run more anti Snake-eyes (or whatever is tier 1) cards if you are going to a YCS. Make adjustments to have a better matchup against the most popular decks. 

Final Notes: 

Runick Fiendsmith Musket is a build I was contemplating but after thorough testing with Runick Muskets in TCG and MD, there are far too many weaknesses to warrant running it with Fiendsmith Musket. You cut Musket S/t to 1 make space for Runick cards, the power cards are (unsurprisingly) more powerful than any of the Runicks, the draw 3 effect of Fountain requires you to draw into Runicks to keep that engine going, and the no BP clause makes the game artifically longer. If Fountain never goes up OR if it goes down, Runick stops working on your opponent's turn. Fiendsmith puts up a lot of damage on board on behalf of the otherwise weak Musketeers, so you can close out games quicker with the non Runick variant. Quicker games, means you grind less in every game, and mitigate the risk of going into time. Also longer games take its toll on you as a player for 9+ round events.

deck_name: All Hands on deck for the Skill Drain Event
deck_excerpt: A fun little realtively cheap deck for the Extreme Duel Skill Drain.
deck_description:
A Quick description of why every card is included:

Battle Fader : Ends the battle phase if you get attacked directly. Pairs well with skill drain, cause no pierce.

Swift Scarecrow : Does the same as Battle Fader only better, since it doesn't leave a body on the field.

Magic Hand : By far the worst card in the deck and only in here because of the hands theme. Replace with any other card if you don't need maximum hands.

Fire Hand : Destroys a monster on destruction and summons an Ice Hand . It needs something to destroy to summon though. NOT once per turn, so if their board is full and you got some life points crash, destroy monster, summon ice, crash, destroy spell/trap, summon fire, crash ...

Ice Hand : Destroys a spell/trap on destruction and summons a Fire Hand . It needs something to destroy to summon though. NOT once per turn, so if their board is full and you got some life points crash, destroy spell/trap, summon fire, crash, destroy monster, summon ice, crash ...

Prominence Hand : Probably the second worst card in the deck, but fairly useful to go into XYZs.

Thunder Hand : Basically a hand trap that triggers on a destruction of a Magic Hand , Fire Hand  or Ice Hand and destroys something while summoning itself.

Lord of the Heavenly Prison : Protects your set cards. If you already have an Imperial Iron Wall going you can set anything and it won't get banished.

Pot of Avarice : Recycles your hands and draws stuff.

Pot of Extravagance : You don't really need your extra deck, draw stuff instead.

Pot of Prosperity :: You don't really need your extra deck, draw stuff instead.

Cauldron of the Old Man : Funnily a real problem for most decks here. Your main win condition.

Waboku : Dying is harder if you don't take battle damage.

Draining Shield : Quick heal, can be replaced.

Imperial Iron Wall : Just a fun addition to be able to search anything with Lord of the Heavenly Prison , sadly deactivates 2 of the pots.

deck_excerpt: Pure Vaal deck post infinite forbidden
deck_description: Runs pure, could add some other synchros or level four stuff but is a good basis for otking and safely building with cross out. Not a lot to fit as the vaal cards can take a lot, but I think the consistency and adaptablility is strong as long as they maintain through hand traps.

Side Deck Not Included.

 

Going First:

Find a way to link into Folgo, Justice Fur Hire, get a way to destroy cards on your opponent's turn such as Donpa, Marksman Fur Hire on field & Rex, Freight Fur Hire in GY, get 2 "Fur Hire"s alongside Folgo on the field to draw 3 cards, and get as many hand traps as possible to basically stop your opponent from playing the game. Alternative options are Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess, Rafale, Champion Fur Hire, & Wiz, Sage Fur Hire for negates.

54.27% chance to open at least 1 hand trap, starter, & "Fur Hire"s to summon according to the yugioh.party calculator

Going Second:

Link climb to Borrelsword Dragon, Borreload Dragon, and/or Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax to end the game or at the very least deal some damage. If you open enough hand traps you can interrupt your opponent which should make this easier. The odds you draw at least two hand traps are pretty high so it's likely you will have interruptions.

68.44% chance to open at least 1 hand trap, starter, & "Fur Hire"s to summon according to the yugioh.party calculator

Other Tools:

There are some neat non-engine tools such as:

Archnemeses Eschatos, which isn't searchable, but when you draw it it's not hard for Fur Hires to summon it and it can be detrimental to decks that rely on one type of monster (i.e HEROs).

I:P Masquerena, Anybody who plays anything competitive knows what this generic link-2 does and it's very self-explanatory, same with Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess, which if you go full combo into has 3-4 negates with Falgo on field.

Knightmare Unicorn, Knightmare Phoenix, & Knightmare Cerberus, generic toolbox cards that have uses. Phoenix destroys backrow, Cerberus destroys monsters, and Unicorn shuffles monsters back into the deck.

 Dharc the Dark Charmer, Gloomy & Hiita the Fire Charmer, Ablaze are primarily used to steal monsters from the graveyard. Unfortunately this build does not run any search targets for Hiita, and only one for Dharc, if you want to play targets and stay Fur Hire, you can run Bravo, Fighter Fur Hire for Hiita and more copies of Seal, Strategist Fur Hire for Dharc. Or you can play other out-of-archetype targets.

deck_excerpt: Guess what will come out of this hat
deck_description:
Skeleton for a trap monster deck. Uses a few monsters that special themselves to get into Top Hat Hare and grab the trap that's missing from your hand, Extrav & Morganite for draw power and extra recovery. The main cast is Anguish that makes every other trap monster summon after it a pop 1, Azurune negates special summons by sending another trap mon, Tiki Soul protects the rest & Tiki Curse helps in battle, Jirai Gumo is a conditional pop 1 by itself, Silhouhatte & Apophis negate monsters, Shapesister is a tuner giving access to synchros, Metamorphortress can convert a spare Red Layer into a 3k beater.

The alternatives include Hamon for a beating, an Eldlich engine, an illusion engine for the thematic-ness, Kiriban & BBS to get her or any other monster, Sanctum protects set backrow on the field, Trap Gather is funny, Magic Planter could be a neat option, Critias could be fun to mess around with as a side thing, Thrust can grab your spells or paleos, Anguish pops on either field so an Artifact engine is valid, Stungray is another monster, as is Metal Reflect Slime which can convert into Egyptian God Slime, and as hinted Paleozoic is also a neat engine to splice.
This is an updated version of the dinosaur deck I want to get.

deck_description: Testing
Don't mind the deck list you see while scrolling cause I put in some new cards so will edit this soon

Trying to make Pure Harpies as consistent and competitve as possible, and I think I did a pretty decent job. Small World helps a lot with getting channeler as often as possible. Trap Trick, which probably should be at 3 copies (swap for 1 Hysteric Party or 1 Small World), is to help get Feather Storm as often as possible, as it is the card that wins you most of your games because of its insane negate effect.

All of the hand traps, aside from Nibiru, that I chose work with Small world since they all only share 1 Type/Attr/Lvl/ATK/DEF with any of the Harpies. So, you can banish the hand trap from your deck to get to channeler. Nibiru is kind of insane with Cyber Slash and could probably be main decked, because you can just bounce the token on the following turn and go in for game, but opted for Droll and Lock Bird for going first. For the extra deck, I don't actually have S:P but if I did I would run it. If you don't have S:P, I would maybe run either Knightmare Unicorn or Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax (which is what I am running).

deck_excerpt: Fire fist your opponent to dust or drop them into the abyss with your Traprrix
deck_description:
This isn't a description, deal with it (this is a technically playable fire fist traptrix deck for HAT format, based on the list used by 

ghostmourner)
Cute Big Animal Warriors
Budget Tenpai Dragon
I need these card ( all the Kuriboh are plain card)
My childhood deck

Utilizing scrap recycler's non opt foolish burial effect, you can set up some of the most impressive orcut boards since TOSS format. Using the horus engine gives the deck the ability to protect itself from handtraps and extend through opponents interaction. It also allows you to send drawn orcust combo pieces from your hand to the graveyard so you can activate their graveyard effects. Also, I would definitely cut 3x scrapyard. its an okay starter but you don't need fossil dig and scrapyard since they do the exact same thing.

Cheapest Tenpai/Sangen deck I could make without butchering the whole thing. This is a great blind second OTK deck, even with prosperity.

Main combo:

Activate Sangen Summoning, add Tenpai Dragon Paidra

Normal Summon Paidra, add Sangen Kaimen

- Battle Phase -

Activate Sangen Kaimen, add and Special Summon Chundra

Attack with Paidra (even if your opponent's monster has higher ATK; it won't be destroyed due to Paidra's effect.) and activate Chundra's effect to Special Summon Fadra

Attack with all monsters (if available)

Paidra Quick Effect to Synchro with Chundra into Bident (Or other Synchros if needed)

Bident Synchro Summon effect to Summon back Chundra

Attack more, activate Fadra to Special Summon back the Paidra

Fadra Quick Effect to Synchro into Transcendent using Bident

Activate Bident to Summon itself

Attack more (again)...

From here, you can make Hieratic Seals and Summon back Transcendent, or Synchro into other guys...

With most combos, you should be able to OTK pretty much every time, except for a few very specific situations in which your opponent is floodgating you.

Note: To deal a bunch of damage, you can also make Kuibelt, destroy the Field Spell and double its ATK.

Enjoy!

deck_excerpt: What happens when two fan favourite graveyard decks mix together?
deck_description:
What happens when two fan favourite graveyard decks mix together? You get Tearlament Lightsworn - the ultimate combination in milling technology! As we near the 2nd anniversary of the release of Tearlaments, we have yet another incredible Tearlament variant. 
 
With the release of Legacy of Destruction, new life has been breathed into the Lightsworn strategy. Dragonling and Archfiend add extra gas and consistency by giving more mills, foolish burials and GY summons. Synchro Minerva offers more targeted "foolish burials" and milling power by banishing up to 4 lightsworns in GY - which by the way makes Punishment Dragon live. Finally, Lightsworn has been gifted by an omni-negate multi-target trap - Lightsworn Aegis! 
 
Add on to the new Lightsworn cards the usual GY fusion milling shenanigans of Horus + Tearlament, and you have an incredible GY powerhouse with enough gas to play through any interruption, handtrap and boardstate! While playtesting this deck, it feels like it is so consistent, powerful and contains so much gas that it feels like playing tier 0 Ishizu Tearlament all over again. If you've missed the thrill of full power "Tear 0," I highly suggest giving Tearlaments Lightsworn a try! It certainly scratched my itch to mill and gamble, and it probably give you the good ol' dopamine rush as well!
 
Mill, mill, mill like never before with Tearlament Lightsworn!
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 

ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING 

 

Forming the core of this strategy, the TEARLAMENT portion of this deck consists of 18 cards. 3 Perlereino allow you to search for the 9 maindeck Tearlament monsters: Scheiren, Havnis, Merrli, 3 Reinoheart and 3 Tearlaments Kashtira. 2 Scream,  and 2 Sulliek. 1 Cryme is included in the Side Deck to side in when you can choose to go 1st. 

 

LIGHTSWORN forms a sizeable portion of this deck, allowing for more mills, bodies and GY interaction. it is composed of __ cards. 

 

A HORUS package is used mainly for turboing out Zombie Vampire for mills and is composed of 6 cards - 3 Imsety, 1 Hapi, and 2 King's Sarcophagus. 

 

A KASHTIRA package of 2 Fenrir and 3 Kashtira Tearlaments are used. Fenrir is simultaneously a combo piece (since it searches for Tear Kash) and a boardbreaker, but only two are used in this deck, since they don't really do anything when milled.

 

You may have noticed that there are hardly any handtraps or generic staples in this deck. The theory behind this build of Tearlaments is that it has so much gas that it can play through all of your opponent's interruptions just fine, as long as your graveyard is accessible and you aren't floodgated to death (most relevant floodgates are at 1 or banned anyways). 

 

40 cards are used to ensure this strategy is as consistent and compact as possible. In addition to bricking less, the mills will have much better results than bigger Tearlaments variants because of the deck's compact size. 

 

COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN 

 

As usual, Tearlaments' gameplan is to mill as much as possible to trigger graveyard effects. Like every Tearlaments strategy, this deck aims to mill as much as possible and gain beneficial effects from those mills. The reliance on mills makes this strategy unpredictable and luck dependant, meaning that there are hardly any straightforward combos. 

 

There are no straightforward "combos" for Tearlament Lightsworn due to the random nature of the deck. Combos are hand/mill dependent - leaving the rest of the game up to the duelists individual skill, decision making and mental fortitude (that's the Tearlaments is considered as a difficult to pilot deck). Tearlaments are also infamous for requiring a great deal of skill, since the pilot has to be aware of the various interactions they have in the GY and the amount of cards left in their main deck. 

 

What differentiates this version of Tearlaments from the others are the Lightsworn cards. Lightsworn allows for more mills, extension, bodies on board, negates, interruption, etc. In short, Lightsworn makes Tearlaments vastly more powerful and consistent than ever before! Try to resolve both of the Synchro Minerva's effects, since her targeted "foolish burials" + mill for 4 adds a lot of momentum and resources to this milling strategy. 

 

Generally, endboards consist of any combination of 2-4 negate Apollousa, S:P Little Knight, Lightsworn monster (typically Minerva) + Lightsworn Aegis, Grapha, Rulkallos, Scream and Sulliek. Depending on your mills (which are often very good thanks to new Lightsworn cards), you can get about 2-10+ interruptions/negates!

 

GENERAL TIPS

  • Horus cards are incredible at cracking established boards and can out powerful boss monsters that have negates/interruption. After clearing your opponent's board, XYZ summon Zombie Vampire with Imsety and Hapi and get milling! 
  • Zombie Vampire not accessible due to no access to the Horus engine? Worry not! Synchro Minerva is a level 8 and Punishment Dragon is a level 8 which you can use to make Zombie Vampire! 
  • Thanks to the accessibility of Synchros with this deck, you can trigger both of Cross-Sheep's ATK increase and summon from the GY when you have a fusion + synchro underneath it's arrows! Be sure to leave the middle MMZ and side MMZs clear for Cross-Sheep's arrows. 
  • You can also synchro summon Visas Amritara to search ANY Tearlament spell/trap, thanks to the Lightsworn cards. All Lightsworns are light monsters and you have plenty of tuners, so summoning this main character is a breeze, adding extra consistency in this deck. 
  • Any Tearlaments strategy is infamous for requiring a great deal of skill to pilot, since the duelists is required to know all the various interactions that goes on in the GY, and to remember how many cards are left in their deck - the while considering how the opponent will react to the plays. This deck is not easy, so practice makes perfect with Tearlaments. 
     
    Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 

CONCLUDING REMARKS

 
LIGHTSWORNS ARE BACK! WE'RE SO BACK! THE LIGHT OF DESTRUCTION IS HERE AND MORE POWERFUL THAN EVER! UNLEASH JUDGMENT AND PUNISHMENT ON YOUR OPPONENTS ONCE AGAIN WITH LIGHTSWORN TEARLAMENT! 
 
The cool thing about combining Tearlaments and Lightsworns is that you now have two waifu decks as one (Schieren and Minerva my beloved ❤️)! Truly peak Yugioh deckbuilding. 
 
During my playtesting, it felt like this deck is so consistent, powerful and contains so much gas that it feels like playing tier 0 Ishizu Tearlament all over again. If you've missed the thrill of full power "Tear 0," I highly suggest giving Tearlaments Lightsworn a try! It certainly scratched my itch to mill and gamble, and it probably give you the good ol' dopamine rush as well! In the words of the Tearlaments guy at Locals, "every mill is like opening a fresh pack of Yugioh cards!" 

 

GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: Synchro Yusei-core but with some quality of life additions
deck_description:
My first deck I've ever made. Very new to the game and like Yusei. Right now I'm only really on 2004 meta ideas so its probably old looking

Just a basic deck that can lead with a starting combo to Junk Speeder/Warrior with some basic all around negation/removal spells and traps. There's some searchers in the deck too in case of a bad starting hand. The extra deck is lacking because I just don't know of alot of synchro cards. I also aimed for being able to buy this in real life without selling a arm and a leg.

Future improvements hopefully: Better tuner composition. Better extra deck. More precise usage of spells and traps. A clearer win condition.

deck_name: Agents Post-LEDE no Baronne Draft 1 by Lenninho
deck_description:
Credit to Lenninho on YT for this list. Currently working on making it my own.

Basic rundown of Agent Fairies: it's a synchro deck that lost Baronne post-April 2024 banlist. So baronne is replaced with Bystial Dis Pater for level 10 synchro and Thunder Dragon Colossus which is now off the forbidden list. Ringowurm and Corridor are added to summon Colossus.

Unique addition of Small World to avoid bricky hands: send Majesty Hyperion from deck to banish as a bridge to your starters.

May test bigger deck sizes to lessen chance of shine ball bricks.

deck_excerpt: Crystal Beast Advanced Crystal Beast Yubel
deck_description:
2.0 of my Dark Crystal Beast variant for the Domain Format. Wanna know what Domain Format is? 

DISCORD LINK https://discord.gg/E9GU5YpW Domain Format requires your deck to have 60 cards in the main deck instead of the usual minimum of 40. You can only run 1 copy of each card in your deck (So you can't play 3 Blue-Eyes White Dragons for example), and you must have a Deck Master, a Monster that exists outside of the Main or Extra deck, meaning it doesn't count to the 60 card main deck limit or 15 card extra deck limit. Your Deck Master determines what other monsters you can play in your deck, depending on it's Type, Attribute, and affiliations with Archetypes aswell as specific cards listed in it's text. If it mentions a Type, Attribute or specific ATK/DEF line (Like 2400ATK/1000 DEF for example) in it's text, you can also include those kinds of monsters in your deck. Deck Masters can be summoned from the Deck Master Zone using their appropriate mechanic (Normal Summon, Tribute Summon, Synchro Summon, etc...) or by using their Inherent Summon effect if your chosen Deck Master has one (An inherent summon is any kind of monster effect that allows the card to special summon itself to the field without starting a chain, easily identifiable by the lack of a ":" or ";" in the effect). Deck Masters can be returned to the Deck Master Zone if they get sent from the field to any other zone, like the graveyard or banishment. You must pay a cumulative cost of 500 life points to summon your Deck Master for each time it has returned to the Deck Master Zone. (1st: 500 LP, 2nd: 1,000 LP, 3rd: 1500 LP, etc...) Cited by: Dracoeyes and their Linkedin article right below this with the link! Check it out its very good for getting into the format! https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/domain-format-guide-1-deck-building-draco-vulpes-we5pc/?trackingId=%2FbU9fD9YS1%2Bq94vuSyjoaA%3D%3D

I took my first adderall for my previously unmedicated ADHD. The result was this deck. This deck IS interruption, you play against this deck you WILL sit and wait while i have 7 activateable effects on your main phase. It never stops, you will sooner run out of cards than you will things to do. Make SURE you run as much of the white woods line as you can before beginning centurion, even though cards like asteria directly synergize with the main starter of centurion. Synergy IS this deck, centurion runs monsters as spell and traps, while being an even number synchro deck, white woods doesnt discriminate with their effects to destroy spells and traps, and with centurion having GY effects hits only makes it better. Small runick package for support, you can see theres a bunch of interesting little lines and parts where you can meld the two decks mid combo. I got a little lucky with some of the draw effect, but so can you! The combo potential is limitless thanks to level 4, 6, 8, 10, and 12 sychros. Learn whitewoods before you learn centurion :)

deck_excerpt: What's the most you can make when you Normal Summon Machina Gearframe?
deck_description:
Deus ex Machina Gearframe or: How I Learned to Stop Worrying and Love the Machine.

This all started with a thought experiment: What's the most I can make when I Normal Summon Machina Gearframe?

I'll start by giving you the combo, then go more in-depth about card choices and alternatives. Apologies in advance for being over-specific with the language, I wanted to make sure that the steps of the combo were clear.

1. Normal Summon Machina Gearframe (#1). Trigger Machina Gearframe (#1); add Machina Unclaspare from your Deck to your Hand. Trigger Machina Unclaspare; Special Summon Machina Unclaspare from your Hand to your Field (you can now only Special Summon Machine Monsters for the rest of the Turn). Trigger Machina Unclaspare; send Machina Ruinforce (or Fortress, or Citadel, but we'll go over that later) from your Deck to your GY.

2. Overlay Machina Gearframe (#1) and Machina Unclaspare to Xyz Summon Gear Gigant X (#1).

3. Detach Machina Gearframe (#1) to activate Gear Gigant X (#1); add Superheavy Samurai Motorbike from your Deck to your Hand.

4. Discard Superheavy Samurai Motorbike to activate Superheavy Samurai Motorbike; add Superheavy Samurai Prodigy Wakaushi from your Deck to your Hand.

5. Activate Superheavy Samurai Prodigy Wakaushi in your Pendulum Zone.

6. Activate Superheavy Samurai Prodigy Wakaushi's effect; Special Summon it to your Field while placing Superheavy Samurai Monk Big Benkei in your other Pendulum Zone.

7. Activate Superheavy Samurai Monk Big Benkei; add Superheavy Samurai Soulgaia Booster from your Deck to your Hand.

8. Activate Superheavy Samurai Soulgaia Booster, targeting Superheavy Samurai Prodigy Wakaushi; equip Superheavy Samurai Soulgaia Booster to Superheavy Samurai Prodigy Wakaushi.

9. Activate Superheavy Samurai Soulgaia Booster; Special Summon Superheavy Samurai Soulgaia to your Field.

This is Phase 1. How to combo spirals from here can vary greatly, but every time you start by Normal Summoning Machina Gearframe, regardless of your end-goal, you usually want to get to this point.

Now, for where my thought experiment splits off from what would be considered this deck's "standard" combo.

10. Overlay Superheavy Samurai Prodigy Wakaushi and Superheavy Samurai Soulgaia Booster to Xyz Summon Gear Gigant X (#2).

11. Detach Superheavy Samurai Prodigy Wakaushi to activate Gear Gigant X (#2); add Infinitrack Harvester from your Deck to your Hand.

12. Use Gear Gigant X (#1) and Gear Gigant X (#2) as material to Link Summon Ancient Gear Ballista to your Extra Monster Zone. Trigger Ancient Gear Ballista; add Ancient Gear Box (that's where the cat goes). Trigger Ancient Gear Box; add Superheavy Samurai General Coral from your Deck to your Hand.

13. Activate Superheavy Samurai General Coral in your Pendulum Zone.

14. Banish Machina Unclaspare, Superheavy Samurai Prodigy Wakaushi and Superheavy Samurai Soulgaia Booster from your GY to Special Summon Machina Ruinforce from your GY.

15. Use Ancient Gear Ballista and Machina Ruinforce as material to Link Summon Qliphort Genius (#1) to your Extra Monster Zone.

16. Pendulum Summon Ancient Gear Box and Infinitrack Harvester to the Zones Qliphort Genius (#1) points to. Trigger Qliphort Genius (#1) (Chain Link 1) and Infinitrack Harvester (Chain Link 2); add Infinitrack Tunneler from your Deck to your Hand and add Therion "King" Regulus from your Deck to your Hand.

17. Activate Therion "King" Regulus, targeting Machina Gearframe (#1) in your GY; Special Summon Therion "King" Regulus from your Hand to your Field (to a Zone other than the Zones Qliphort Genius (#1) points to) and equip Machina Gearframe (#1) to Therion "King" Regulus.

18. Activate Machina Gearframe (#1); Special Summon Machina Gearframe (#1) to your Field.

19. Overlay Ancient Gear Box and Machina Gearframe to Xyx Summon Gear Gigant X (#3).

20. Detach Machina Gearframe to activate Gear Gigant X (#3); add Machina Gearframe (#2) from your Deck to your Hand.

21. Tribute Gear Gigant X (#3) to activate Infinitrack Tunneler; Special Summon Infinitrack Tunneler from your Hand to your Field in Defense Position.

22. Activate Infinitrack Harvester, Targeting Infinitrack Tunneler; make the Levels of both Infinitrack Harvester and Infinitrack Tunneler Level 7.

23. Overlay Infinitrack Harvester and Infinitrack Tunneler to Xyz Summon Mecha Phantom Beast Dracossack (to a Zone other than the Zones Qliphort Genius (#1) points to).

24. Detach Infinitrack Tunneler to activate Mecha Phantom Beast Dracossack; Special Summon two Mecha Phantom Beast Tokens to the Zones Qliphort Genius (#1) points to. Trigger Qliphort Genius (#1); add Machina Irradiator from your Deck to your Hand.

25. Use the two Mecha Phantom Beast Tokens as material to Link Summon Qliphort Genius (#2) to a Zone Qliphort Genius (#1) points to (This can also be Barricadeborg Blocker if you use one of the Mecha Phantom Beast Tokens and Mecha Phantom Beast Dracossack).

26. Use Qliphort Genius (#1) and Qliphort Genius (#2) as material to Link Summon Amphibious Swarmship Amblowhale to your Extra Monster Zone.

27. Banish Infinitrack Tunneler from your GY to activate Infinitrack Tunneler's effect, targeting Gear Gigant X (#1), Gear Gigant X (#2), Gear Gigant X (#3), Qliphort Genius (#1) and Qliphort Genius (#2); return Gear Gigant X (#1), Gear Gigant X (#2), Gear Gigant X (#3), Qliphort Genius (#1) and Qliphort Genius (#2) to your Extra Deck ("shuffle them into the Deck"), then Draw two cards from your Deck.

28. Use Amphibious Swarmship Amblowhale and Mecha Phantom Beast Dracossack as material to Link Summon Qliphort Genius (#1) to your Extra Monster Zone.

29. Discard Machina Gearframe (#2) to activate Machina Irradiator's effect; Special Summon Machina Irradiator from your Hand to your Field (to a Zone other than the Zones Qliphort Genius points to).

30. Banish Machina Gearframe (#1), Ancient Gear Box, Infinitrack Harvester, and Superheavy Samurai Motorbike from your GY to Special Summon Machina Ruinforce from your GY (to a Zone Qliphort Genius points to).

31. Activate Machina Irradiator's effect, targeting Machina Ruinforce; Special Summon Machina Gearframe (#2) from your GY (to a Zone other than the Zones Qliphort Genius points to) and Destroy Machina Ruinforce. Trigger Machina Ruinforce; Special Summon Machina Gearframe (#1) and Machina Unclaspare from your Banishment to the Zones Qliphort Genius points to. Trigger Qliphort Genius; add Heavy Freight Train Derricrane from your Deck to your Hand.

32. Overlay Machina Gearframe (#1) and Machina Gearframe (#2) to Xyz Summon Gear Gigant X (#1).

33. Detach Machina Gearframe (#1) to activate the effect of Gear Gigant X (#1); add Flying Pegasus Railroad Stampede from your Deck to your Hand.

34. Use Gear Gigant X (#1) and Qliphort Genius (#1) as material to Link Summon Platinum Gadget to your Extra Monster Zone.

35. Use Machina Unclaspare and Machina Irradiator as material to Link Summon Double Headed Anger Knuckle to a Zone Platinum Gadget points to. Trigger Heavy Freight Train Derricrane; Special Summon Heavy Freight Train Derricrane from your Hand to your Field.

36. Banish Machina Gearframe (#1), Machina Gearframe (#2), and Machina Unclaspare from your GY to Special Summon Machina Ruinforce from your GY.

37. Overlay Machina Ruinforce and Heavy Freight Train Derricrane to Xyz Summon Number 81: Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Super Dora.

38. Activate Platinum Gadget; Special Summon Flying Pegasus Railroad Stampede from your Hand to your Field. Trigger Flying Pegasus Railroad Stampede; Special Summon Machina Irradiator from your GY.

39. Activate Flying Pegasus Railroad Stampede, Targeting Machina Irradiator; make the Level of Flying Pegasus Railroad Stampede Level 8.

40. Overlay Flying Pegasus Railroad Stampede and Machina Irradiator to Xyz Summon Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star. Trigger Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star; attach Infinitrack Tunneler from your Banishment to Dingirsu, Orcust of the Evening Star.

End-Board:

- Therion "King" Regulus (Omni-Negate)

- Number 81: Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Super Dora with Heavy Freight Train Derricrane as Xyz Material (4000 Defense and can make any Monster a Towers, detaching Heavy Freight Train Derricrane will trigger Heavy Freight Train Derricrane's effect to target and destroy an opponent's card)

- Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star with 3 Xyz Materials, including Infinitrack Tunneler (Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star can prevent the destruction of a card(s) by detaching an Xyz Material, and Infinitrack Tunneler can Banish itself to shuffle five EARTH Machine Monsters from your GY into your Deck (or Extra Deck) and then draws two cards from your Deck)

- Double Headed Anger Knuckle (can send any Monster from your Hand or Field to the GY in order to Special Summon a Level 10 Machine Monster from your GY, we'll come back to this)

- Platinum Gadget (doesn't really do anything at this point, we'll come back to this too)

- Superheavy Samurai Monk Big Benkei (Pendulum Scale)

- Superheavy Samurai General Coral (Pendulum Scale)

- Two cards drawn from your Deck.

Total Cards: 9

Total Advantage: +8

Total Interruptions: ~4 (Therion "King" Regulus, Number 81: Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Super Dora, Heavy Freight Train Derricrane, Amphibious Swarmship Amblowhale in your GY)

Other Board Presence: Pendulum Scales, Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star can detach Xyz Materials to prevent any of your card(s) from being destroyed by battle or card effects, Double Headed Anger Knuckle can revive a level 10 from your GY by sending an otherwise useless card like Platinum Gadget to the GY.

Now for the technical stuff.

Strengths, Weaknesses, Highlights and Combo Notes.

Strengths:

- Ending on most of the usual End-Board but coupled with a Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star while recycling Infinitrack Tunneler gives the board a lot of protection while enabling follow-up.

- This combo is the absolute most I can produce (for now) - any 1-time interruption theoretically limits some of what I can produce, but between extenders and draw power most interruptions can be played around, or at the very least put up everything an the End-Board bar DIngirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star, which is what the deck was already doing anyway.

- Despite the write-up, I'm still working on the combo, I just wanted to flag my progress after finally assembling an End-Board that included the usual fare of Therion "King" Regulus, Number 81: Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Super Dora and Double Headed Anger Knuckle with the theoretically incredible value of summoning Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star and attaching the previously banished Infinitrack Tunneler so that I can re-use it without having to include Machina Overdrive in the Deck (that's another conversation).

Weaknesses:

- The combo itself is extremely fragile because it's so self-sufficient (fuel-efficient?); a Bystial/D.D. Crow on Ruinforce or even Wakaushi or Unclaspare starves the combo of the resources it uses - I guess it's a good thing it has so many extenders, but that also turns a lot of First-Turns into coin-flips.

- The nature of the deck heavily limits your tech options; a deck that's as combo-heavy as this desperately needs strong tech to help with going second and dealing with interruptions, but the Superheavy Samurai engine means no Called by the Grave or Crossout Designator to stop Hand Traps, no Triple Tactics Talent/Triple Tactics Thrust to punish Hand Traps, no Forbidden Droplet, Dark Ruler No More, Lightning Storm or Evenly Matched to break the opponent's Board - sure, we have Hand Traps of our own, and there are a couple of Monster Board Breakers like Kashtira Fenrir, Dinowrestler Pankratops, and Kaiju Monsters, but such a heavy limiting of options will radically affect the type of meta a deck like this can perform in, and other combo decks do the sort of degenerate things that this deck does without that sort of handicap. That doesn't mean I'll stop playing the deck, nor does it mean that you should, it's just a pretty heavy concession to take on when building around this combo. If a Gear Gigant X search that's less restrictive and more potent than Superheavy Samurai Prodigy Wakaushi gets released, I'll re-visit this point.

- An extension of the second problem this deck has is the problem the deck has with going second. While it can easily pull off an OTK and the Hand Traps usually provide it with what it needs to prevent the opponent from setting up a board (just remember that most Hand Traps are low-impact by themselves, try to use them in conjunction with one another and be selective about when and how you use them, don't mindlessly throw your Ash Blossom away - Ash Blossom is used specifically to counter Maxx "C" in the OCG, so in any given match-up, try to figure out the opponent's Maxx "C" you're holding your Ash Blossom for), this is a "Weaknesses" section so I'm trying to emphasise the difficulties the deck can experience. This isn't the Top Meta Deck, it's not even a footnote, you can't be mindless in 90% of match-ups and expect to win anyway.

Alright, that's enough negativity.

Highlights:

- The combo uses Gear Gigant X's effect four times and Qliphort Genius' effect three times. "Once per turn" is just a mindset.

- The combo starts with Machina Gearframe or Superheavy Samurai Motorbike, but can't do it with one card if you start with Machina Redeployment or Superheavy Samurai Prodigy Wakaushi; ironically, the stronger starters are "weaker" in the context of this particular combo.

- My goal was the find a way to make Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star so that I could recover Infinitrack Tunneler, all without having to start with more than Machina Gearframe. I have succeeded in that goal.

Combo Notes:

- The "standard" version of this combo ends on Therion "King" Regulus, Number 81: Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Super Dora (with Heavy Freight Train Derricrane attached), Double Headed Anger Knuckle and Gigantic "Champion" Sargas (with Infinitrack Goliath attached), as well as the standard draw two from Infinitrack Tunneler, and Machina Citadel in the GY, which you can pre-emptively set up with Number 81: Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Super Dora and Gigantic "Champion" Sargas if you commit one more Monster (any monster will do) to the combo. Amphibious Swarmship Amblowhale is a poor substitute for Machina Citadel, but I'll take the trade-off of Gigantic "Champion" Sargas and Machina Citadel for Ampibious Swarmship Amblowhale and Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star and a recycled Infinitrack Tunneler, at least for now while I try to find ways to clean up the combo.

- Machina Irradiator is the progenitor of this version of the combo. Essentially each enabler in the combo has a sort of "break-point" where I determine exactly what I can do and what would be best to do in order to achieve my goal (in this case, ending on the "standard" board but with Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star to recycle Infinitrack Tunneler). Machina Gearframe and Machina Unclaspare interact with a "Machina" Monster, Qliphort Genius interacts with Level 5 or higher Machine Monsters, and Infinitrack River Stormer interacts with EARTH Machine Monsters (Infinitrack River Stormer, sadly, did not make the final cut of the current build; it's too inefficient without Infinitrack Brutal Dozer, and Infinitrack Brutal Dozer locks you into EARTH Machine Monsters, and getting out Infinitrack Tunneler without Infinitrack Brutal Dozer and getting Dingirsu, Orcust of the Evening Star and still getting out Infinitrack Brutal Dozer, while also having any space in the Extra Deck, is very hard, at least while committing to the stipulations of the thought experiement). I kept coming across Machina Irradiator as a result of looking at cards within these filters, and regularly dismissed it because I held that it was a bad card. I still do, to be honest, but in addition to its role in the combo, I've found it to be a useful search for Machina Gearframe when you open Machina Unclaspare, or even just opening with Machina Unclaspare in general.

- There are many, many, many cards that I have considered in the process of assembling this combo, the most obvious being the Orcust cards themselves, but in addition to having to run too many cards that could easily be bricks, locking you into Machines so early means that you can't make I:P Masquerana for Orcust's big Turn-Two play. I'll keep toying with things though, this is a work-in-progress. 

If you've come this far, you might enjoy a little story about my journey with Machina (I guess if recipes can have them, deck recipes can have them too).

The reason I started working on this combo is because Machina Fortress is my favourite combo of all time and, by extension, Machina Gearframe is my favourite card to Normal Summon.

Machina was the first deck I ever topped a tournament with back in 2013, during Dragon Ruler Format; don't worry, it was the second phase of Dragon Ruler Format, after the babies were banned, I was using Redox myself, I only faced/defeated one Dragon Ruler player in Swiss, and I immediately lost in Top Cut, it just sounds more impressive when I reduce it to "I topped a tournament with Machina during Dragon Ruler Format"... something I also did with Battlin' Boxers, but that's a story for another time.

The point is that I have a long history with Machina. Even after I dropped out of the game in 2014 with the introduction of Pendulum Monsters (I don't have a particular bias against the Pendulum mechanic, I was just already losing enthusiasm in the game and the introduction of a new mechanic made that transition out of the game easier), I still held deep in my heart the sheer joy I found in the degeneracy of Machina Fortress being able to discard itself as part of the cost of its own summon by its own [unclassified effect], and being able to repeatedly revive it by discarding level 8 Machine Monsters (like I said, this was Dragon Ruler(-adjacent) Format, being able to summon Mecha Phantom Beast Dracossack was the name of the game, detaching a Fortress only to revive it again hit different in 2013 - sidebar: Does anyone else say "Machine Monster" in their head like Joey did in his duel with Bandit Keith?).

When I got back into the game in late 2020/early 2021 (between Phantom Rage and Blazing Vortex) the only deck I was interested in was "the best deck that runs Machina Fortess." Obviously my attention was turned to Earth Machines and the then-dead Orcust. While I was happy to be playing my favourite card again, the base Earth Machine build at the time was little more than Anger Knuckle Turbo; it wasn't the deck's fault, so to speak, the cards just weren't there yet for a truly combo-heavy Earth Machine deck to emerge. Then the new Supherheavy Samurai support came out, and after playing it to death until the banning of Superheavy Samurai Scarecrow, I realised that Superheavy Samurai Prodigy Wakaushi/Superheavy Samurai Motorbike were able to produce a Gear Gigant X without using your Normal Summon. The fact that you can start there and get to Machina Gearframe, or start with Machina Gearframe and get to Superheavy Samurai Prodigy Wakaushi/Superheavy Samurai Motorbike, is just gravy for me - I love combos that flow into each other like that, for a while I tinkered with a Libromancer P.U.N.K. deck because I worked out a combo that could start either with the Libromancer side or the P.U.N.K. side and it would inevitably develop into the other, though I haven't revisited it since the banning of Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights, but I digress.

If you read this far, I thank you for your time. If you have any advice on more optimal routes I could take to still end up with a recycled Infinitrack Tunneler (which itself was the whole point of getting to Dingirsu, not just recycling it but having it back immediately) and/or more threatening End-Board that I haven't already mentioned, let me know.

Good luck and Godspeed to anyone who tries this degenerate insanity.

Witchcrafter Fusion Control

This deck combines the resource management and control aspects of the Witchcrafter archetype with powerful Fusion monsters for an explosive mid-range strategy.

Core Engine:

  • Witchcrafters: The deck focuses on utilizing the Witchcrafter monsters' spell-like effects to gain advantage, searching for spells and manipulating your opponent's hand and field.
  • Branded Fusion & Fusion Spells: Branded Fusion allows for powerful Fusion Summons like Albion the Branded Dragon, while Red-Eyes Fusion and Witchcrafter Creation offer alternative Fusion options.

Tech Choices:

  • Dark Magician & Red-Eyes Black Dragon: These classic monsters provide additional Fusion material and nostalgia value.
  • Hand Traps: Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, Effect Veiler, and Infinite Impermanence disrupt your opponent's plays.
  • Disruption: Called by the Grave and Super Polymerization offer removal against problematic cards.
  • Pot of Prosperity: Provides card advantage and fuels the Witchcrafter effects.

Extra Deck:

The Extra Deck features a variety of Fusion monsters, including:

  • Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon: A powerful negation effect disrupts your opponent's plays.
  • Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon: A boss monster with high ATK and removal capabilities.
  • Albion the Branded Dragon: A strong Fusion with negation and burn effects.
  • Witchcrafter Vice-Madame: A support monster for the Witchcrafter archetype.

Overall, this deck aims to control the game through hand disruption and spell effects, culminating in powerful Fusion Summons to overpower your opponent.

deck_excerpt: Combining Chimera with Runick gives you two amazing advantage engines to outpace your opponent!
deck_description:
Runick's latest and strongest bestie to hang out with is "Chimera," the newest fusion archetype from Masterduel pack Nightmare Arrivals.  

Chimera is an incredible advantage engine capable of overwhelming your opponent with so much resources, interactions and draw power - represented in a fusion deck! For example, one Mirror Swordknight is a whopping +7 in card advantage! 

Combined with Runick, another amazing advantage engine, you get an extremely competent meta strategy that will quickly outpace your opponents! Piloted correctly and skillfully, Chimera Runick will win you games vs. the top decks of the metagame!
 
This deck may be straightforward, but it rewards good decision making since boards and gamestates are determined by the pilot's skill and resource management. If you're a player who likes a resource-based control-focused grindgame, Runick Chimera is the deck for you.

If you want an in-depth guide to this deck complete with combos, check out my guide from last year by clicking here.

GLHF Duelists!

deck_description: Today win local tournament with this.

Source: https://twitter.com/Sm0lScout/status/1784413721395159306

Tenpai deck that I took to Bainbridge for the regional on April 27th.

The deck is very straight forward, setup your protected board with the field spell and climb through monsters during the battle phase to hopefully OTK. Having only 14 engine cards leaves a lot of room for handtraps and boardbreakers. I opted for Cosmic Cyclone in the main to deal with Runick Stun, which I saw none of, but it also helped against decks like Centurion and Voiceless. I don't think there's too much in the main deck I would alter at this moment.

In the extra deck I'd definitely want to add in Timelord Progenitor Vorpgate, since it can handle the potential boards that yubel can end on. 

In the side, I think I'd look for a way to squeeze in Crossout Designator and Dimensional Barrier. A lot of players chose to go first when losing game 1 at the event just to try and dig for a copy, and it was the biggest detriment I ended up having to deal with through most of my matches, when it showed up.

Board breaker with potential OTK. Very cheap main deck, can sub out S:P and TY-PHON to keep overall price ~$100.

Basic Combo (Going 2nd when opponent has 3+ face-ups):

  1. Activate Baatistina, send Sentinel to GY and SS Crystal God
  2. Activate Crystal God's effect
  3. SS Sentinel from GY, activate effect sending itself back to GY to search Demigod
  4. SS Demigod, search Play
  5. XYZ summon Divinity and wipe board
  6. Activate Divinity effect, attack for 4000
  7. Set Play and pass

This deck is a standard Ragnaraika package with some Beetrooper support.

Almost every Ragnaraika card in the MD gets you started so it's very easy to play through hand traps. One of the biggest problems I came across with Ragnaraika was that it crumbled to destruction. If it survives turn 2 (which isn't likely), it can easily build itself back up but to counter that I've included "Sacred Tree Beast, Hyperyton" made with "Rikka Queen Strenna".

The endboard goal is going to be Beargram or Scary Moth alongside the Ragnaraika trap, Hyperyton, and the Ragnaraika link 4 and/or 5 depending on you're opponent's deck.

deck_excerpt: Tired of bricking? This one's for you.
deck_description:
The long story short is that Branded in High Spirits, Golden Swordsoul, and the Vestals help make up for what Tear has lost by providing easy Tuner and Follow-Up Access. This is one of the smoothest functioning Tear builds I've been able to make since Merrli was banned, and the brick rate is extremely low. Trivikarma is a fantastic mill, but too often do I find it losing me games in my hand. Easy access to Amritara through the Vestals convinced me that I could cut it.

The main goal was to make the collective Kitkallos & Tearkash mills just as explosive and consistent as before the deck was hit hard on the banlist. While this goal was certainly unachievable, it's the best solution I've found to this problem and can still open and unlock extremely oppressive plays on the opponent's turn after a Kitkallos-Sulliek pass Maxx "C" turn, let alone when left to free-play.

Golden Swordsoul can banish from field or GY to summon a Vestal from GY or hand. Eccelsia can also tutor one out, and triggering this effect is extremely natural by way of Shufflers, Malicious, Redoer (detach Golden or Golden already in GY) and Link a self-revived Reinoheart for Cross Sheep. You can also Special Summon it going second using your Battle Phase and a Normal Summon if things get dire (this is usually how Golden ends up under Redoer), and sometimes you get lucky and a Fader is just enough to survive to the next turn, recycle GY effects and top deck for game. The second one does come up, and it comes up quite often. I've rarely found myself wanting a third.

Quem, Cartesia & Cross Sheep generate ludricrous amounts of advantage. As an example, if you can link summon Cross Sheep with Quem on board, you can revive Cartesia, summon Granguignol (Dump Malicious), Cross Sheep to revive Quem and end with the ability to revive Cartesia on the opponent's turn to trigger Cross Sheep at a moment's notice. Cartesia also lets you get double value for your Tear names, sending them to the GY for effect while summoning a Fusion herself (Typically Granguignol or Dragostapelia)

High Spirits can send Rullkalos with a Tear Name (or Nessie, though this rarely is worth it) to fusion Kitkallos and can send any Spellcaster and Granguignol to fetch any of the Vestals. The preferred Vestal changes depending on the current hand, field, GY and even opponent's board and chains, most notably because Granguignol can banish itself to tutor Quem from the deck making it better to grab Golden or Ecclesia.

Cartesia, Ecclesia, and High Spirits all recycle themselves if a Fusion is sent to the GY. Maximize this interaction for best results. In long games, Cartesia and Ecclesia can make Amritara on their own.

The ratios in this deck are extremely fragile, and the only card that I think is up for debate in my opinion is the third Scream. It could conceivably be Bystial Aluber to Special Summon Cartesia or Fairy Tail Snow, though you recycle resources so much in this deck that there's not much fuel for Snow to banish. My argument against Aluber is that if I'm playing a card I exclusively want to mill, I should re-insert Trivikarma; Though this argument isn't fully valid as you can still pitch Aluber for cards like Scheiren and Cryme and dump it with Saronir. My argument against Druiswurm is that it's only useful if you draw exactly it or Magnamhut and it is more likely going to get used against you by your opponent's Dharc lines. There is an argument to play Psy-Framelord Omega to close out games and recycle important resources in long, stalled-out games or in games where your cards are getting banished by monsters like Kashtira Fenrir & Unicorn, but I just don't think there's anything in the Extra that you can cut to include it.

I recognize that this deck takes a LOT of UR investment, but in my experience so far it works and works well. If you need to make some budget cuts to work your way up to it, here are some changes that will make the deck worse but a more affordable investment/transition:

Shaddolls Beast, Squamata, and Hollow can help you fill out 40 and give you Winda access if you have her already, and are more Spellcaster pitches for High Spirits. However, I don't know if Winda is necessary.
Play another Droplet and/or 1 Triple Tac if you have them
Amritara mostly comes up in specific hands and grind games, feel free to craft it last and use cards like Dharc and Knightmare Phoenix in the meantime
Some other cards that can fill the Extra if you have them are Chaos Angel, Garura, Exciton Knight
If you're really strapped for Extra deck cards, you can play one of the 2500 Atk SR Hero Fusions as a High Spirits target for Reinoheart and Malicious
Craft Cartesia & Granguinol before Quem
Card Destruction if you've pulled it from the Legacy packs
Gammeciel is a funny Aqua if you're running into a mass of Purrely and/or unable to craft Goddess
If you already have Trivikarma, feel free to play it if you think you need it or just need to fill out 40 cards
Throw your Ash Blossoms in if you're REALLY strapped for cards

deck_description: TENPAI META DECK 1 PLACE TOURNAMENT

A deck profile I made to get this deck as playable as I can without the key cards (as per the title). It is play-tested in my locals scene, with some success beating SE or Tenpai (set Albaz -> Lenatus). It has some recovery options and there's a small bystial package in the side deck if needed. the staples are very much META dependent, but the core doesn't change as much. Whatever you do with this list, DO NOT take out ash and imperms, UNLESS you already have the TTT package. I'd like to lean more towards a 40 card profile, since I hate 50+ profiles. Have fun with it, as it's the best I can think of with the budget I worked with.

Have you ever dreamed to play a yubel deck but you can't afford the new support cards? Now it's out a playable yubel deck that count a single UR and guess what? It was even a Stab ( Foolish Burial ). You need the nephthys cards to pop the yubel in you're hand and you can search out Yubel with Three-Eyed Ghost. For summon Yubel you can use Opening of the Spirit Gates , that's searchable with Dark Beckoning Beast , and create a loop.

Only one little warning; having two Yubel - Terror Incarnate at the same time isn't that good, one of them pop the other.

Enjoy the deck and have fun.

deck_excerpt: Visas Samsara has been released, further increasing the power of Mannadium!
deck_description:
The third wave of Mannadium cards in Masterduel arrived, and while not as impactful as the earlier cards, Visas Samsara from "Nightmare Arrivals" counts as an additional 1 card starter for the deck! With Superheavy Samurai severely weakened by the banlist and Cyberse Mathmech some consistency, Mannadium remains as the only full power combo deck!

Visas Amritara (searches any card with his name) and Trisukta (Enables 1 card combos makes Mannadium more resilient to interruption, less bricky and incredibly powerful. Since consistency has been turned up a notch, there is more room for staples so that you can come out on top of the ever annoying "Maxx C" minigame. You can also fit more handtraps to weaken opposing decks you can combo off in your own turn!

 

The strength of Mannadium that separates it from other combo decks comes from it's natural ability to smash through established boards with in-engine cards like Vicious Astraloud, Planet Reichphobia, Baronne De Fleur and Accesscode. Combined with a critical mass of handtraps and boardbreakers, Mannadium can play through any strategy!

 

 As a result, the Mannadium strategy of summoning a lot of negate-oriented boss monsters turn 1 is has been thoroughly streamlined and made much easier. 

If you want a thorough guide with combos on how to pilot this deck, check out my earlier article. 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: You wanna have fun playing Roids in a different way? Go for it I guess.
deck_description:
You may be looking at this list and thinking that this guy is insane. I am but combining the subpar Roids and the competent Machinas has actually been pretty fun.

The main starter is either Gearframe or Redeployment (To search Gearframe), searching Unclaspare to dump a Machina while going into Gigant to search typically a Roid. From there you kind of just say good luck. The deck mostly wants to utilize the combination of Machinas and Roids to generate resources, get some fusions in, and hit hard. The Roids definetely do hurt the Machina part more than help, but the deck has a couple of neat interactions that can actually snag a few games. Despite everything, Machinas are able to help with constant field presence and interruption (Citadel) while helping with big numbers and access to big Rank 10s. The Roids can actually pull of neat plays in their own right as well, Mixeroid can help facilitate rank 4 plays, Dragonroid adds consistency, and Express can help recoup recources and lead into fusion via adding back discarded materials. The deck is pretty simple and is 100% not going to have any chance against the meta, but it's a pretty fun deck to mess around with if you have a soft spot for Roids.

Funny Stuff- Dragonroid can help facilitate constant materials to summon Ruinforce by being Level 9 and being easily discardable for Roid searches. Having a Mobile Base on board is good for having a massive body, but also can lead to an easy Rank 10 play. Megaroid City's search affect can help trigger Citadel if you pop an EARTH machine for cost, it's a neat combo. Mixeroids second effect combined with the massive amount of machines that end up in grave can clutch games, it's a funny card. Since Vehicroid Connection Zone prevents destruction, you can target a fusion summoned with Connection Zone with Citadel to nuke the field without loosing your fusion (This same logic applies with Overdrive because the pop effect isnt cost)

Other Stuff- You can alter the build to stray away from fusions adding in different roids like Armoroid to fuel Fortress and to make way for more generic staples. You can swap out Submarineroid and Steamroid for Stealthroid and Truckroid to make the main fusion Stealth Union, you can also remove Jumbo Drill for another Extra Deck slot. Honestly its probably the better option giving you access to equip removal, but I like the Drill because its funny.

Good Luck and Have Fun playing Machina Roids.

deck_excerpt: Combo Control Deck with the new Raikas
deck_description:
This deck uses 3 different engines to be able to consistently create huge negate/pop boards and/or create a one-sided bagooska lock. 49 cards is ideal with our amount of garnets and starters, but I can't bring myself to remove another card right now.

The most common Snake Rain pile is going to be Nauya, Nunu, Keurse, Armored Lizard. This gets you to Stag Sovereign, Sunavalon, and the related traps.

Combo: SS Nunu - SS Keurse and Nauya by T Nunu - Nauya activate search Daybreak - Daybreak Keurse - Link Skeletal Soldier using tokens - use Skeletal to SS Armored Lizard - Xyz KotFB - Search Serpentine Princess by sending Armored Lizard to GY - NS Princess - Link Mantis with 1 token and Skeletal Soldier - search Raika trap - SS Skeletal Soldier by sending Princess to the deck - use Princess to SS Samurai Beetle - Link Stag Sovereign using both Raika link monsters - Link Skeletal Soldier using 1 token and Samurai Beetle - use Samurai Beetle to SS Armored Lizard - Link Alien Shocktrooper - Link Sunavalon - search Sunavalon trap

This is 9 pops, and a full board negate.

Alternative pile is Nunu, Nauya, Keurse, NSS

Combo: SS NSS - SS Keurse and Nauya by T NSS - Nauya search Daybreak - SS Nunu - Xyz KotFB - KotFB search Evoltile Megachirella - Daybreak on Keurse - Link Alien Shocktrooper using tokens - NS Megachirella - activate T itself to SS Lios - Lios search Evo trap - Lios send Misc to GY - Activate Misc to SS Animadorned - Animadorn pop Lios to search starter for next turn - Link Echidna using Animadorned and a token - Link Cosmic Slicer using Echidna and a token - Search alien trap - Activate Evo trap to SS Lars in Opp's Draw Step

This is a quick effect Raigeki, a one-sided Bagooska, and 2 omni-negates.

Which combo is better depends on what the Opp is playing and what garnets you have stuck in hand/banished. The Raika line is better going second with a Dark Ruler No More to shut off the Opp's board.
