deck_excerpt: Adventurer Spright  / Rosemont WCQ Regional Top 8
deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Sathe Ali Khaldi

Tournament: Rosemont WCQ Regional – April 28th 2024

Placement: Top 8

Hello there , i present to you my Dogmatika Deck that i’ve been cooking for a while now , i will explain the utility of the cards used and how to play the deck , i hope you will enjoy it !

 

Main deck Monsters :

 

Gen the Diamond Tiger x3 , Ken the Warrior Dragon x1  : Those card are very important for the beginning of our combo : . Gen will do A LOT of things for the deck : It can special summon Ken to your opponent’s field from the deck or hand , which allow us to draw 2 and discard 1 because of Ken’s effect (potencially removing puppet from your hand if you drew it , and get the rest of the starters) , then because Ken is on your opponent’s field , you can use Triple Tactics Talent/Trust to discard 1 card form your opponent’s hand (because Nibiru can be very dangerous) AND it allow our Dogmatikamatrix to search 1 extra card ! Gen can then be used to make almiraj then secure gardna (i will explain later why)

 

Dogmatika Fleurdelis x1 : It’s always nice to have a negate in your hand when you have already the rest of the card you need , which can later be turn into dragoon with duality

 

Dogmatika Maxiumus x1 : You will mostly search it with Dogmatikamatrix , then summon it by banning almiraj (or garura) from your GY. He can send to the GY Herald of the arc light and either Titaniklad/Albion the Branded Dragon to search Alba zoa/Dogmatikalamity. Maximus can be turn later on into Dragoon using Duality.

 

Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous x3 : This card is one of the starters of the deck , you can special summon it when a monster from the extra deck is on the field , it work well with Gen which will be turned into secure gardna. You will mostly use her to search Dogmatikamaxtrix , but you can search something else if you already have it

 

Ash x3 : Negate our opponent and use it with crossout if needed

 

Droll x1 , Nibiru x1 : To protects us with Crossout

 

Gimmick Puppet Nightmare x1 : You will send it to the GY with Granguignol’s effect or by discarding with Ken’s effect if you drew it. You will later on your opponent’s turn special summon it with Albion the sanctifier Dragon on your opponent’s field to lock them for the rest of the turn

 

Fallen of Albaz x1 : You’ll need it in your hand for Cartesia’s effect and for Branded in red. Or if you’re in a bad situation , you can use it’s effect to summon MirrorJade with a opponent’s monster (but be careful to not lock you from special summoning from the extra with Dogmatika’s effect such as Maximus , Ecclesia or Nadir Servant.) You mostly gonna search this card with Titaniklad’s effect

 

Dogmatika Alba Zoa x1 : A 4000 ATK/DEF monster which send your opponent’s extra deck to the GY , it also protects other dogmatika monster (and itself) from extra deck monster’s activated effect. You will summon it with Dogmatikalamity by sending Despian Luluwalilith to the GY (Lulu will also special summon cartesia at the end phase)

 

Blazing Cartesia,The Virtuous x1 : You’ll need her during your opponent’s turn after summoning her with Luluwalilith’s effect. She will summon Granguignol with herself and Albaz (very important to use albaz), Granguignol will then send Puppet to the GY and Branded in Red will target Albaz (we can target Luluwalilith but i will NOT trigger the fusion effect because she will not be added to our hand) to summon Albion the Sanctifire Dragoon for the Puppet lock.

 

White Relic of Dogmatika x1 : To be honnest , i think we could remove her because we use her rarely (it depends of the situation) but i managed once to summon her with the rest of the combo without using gen (because i haven’t drew it but i was very lucky to have everything else in my hand to do the combo)

 

Spells and Traps :

 

Dogmatikamatrix x3 : It’s a key card for the deck. You will mostly search it with Ecclesia , and because of the fact that we summon Ken to the opponent’s field , we can search both Dogmatiakalamity/Alba Zoa AND Maximus (or something else if you already have it). When you have Alba Zoa on your field , you can use it to send what you need in the GY (We need Titaniklad (if you don’t have Albaz in hand) Albion the Branded Dragon (if you don’t have Branded in Red in hand) and Luluwalilith (which is already in the GY because of Dogmatikalamity) OR remove 1 card of YOUR CHOISE from your opponent’s extra deck.

 

Nadir Servant x3 : It can search Ecclesia or Maximus (if you already have Ecclesia) and send either Titaniklad , Garura or Albion the Branded Dragon to the GY. That a is also a starter.

 

Reinforcement of the Army x1 : It is basically a fourth Gen or a bait for Ash if you already have Gen

 

Triples Tactics Thrust x3 : It is triggered by Ken’s effect and can search Nadir servant to get our starter , Triples Tactics Thrust to discard 1 card from our opponent’s hand (to prevent nibiru) or Dogmatika Punishment

 

Triple Tactics Talent x1 : It is triggered by Ken’s effect and allow us to prevent nibiru , control 1 monster of our opponent or draw 2

 

Branded in Red x1 : You mostly gonna set it with Albion the Branded Dragon’s effect to make Albion the Sanctifire Dragon after sending Puppet to the GY with granguignol. You will have to target Albaz from our GY after using him with Cartesia (we can target Luluwalilith but i will NOT trigger the fusion effect because she will not be added to our hand)

 

Called by the grave x1 : It protects us from Ash/droll

 

Crossout Designator x3 : It protects us from Ash/droll/nibiru/called by the grave or prevent our opponent of using Triple Tactics Thrust

 

Duality x3 : You cannot search this card , but if you’re lucky enough to draw it , you can set it to tribute either Maximus/Fleudelis/Granguinol and summon Dragoon. Also , it can shuffle back in the deck 1 light and 1 dark monster from the GY and draw 1.

 

Dogmatikalamity x1:Search it with Herald of the Arc Light or Dogmatikamatrix , use it to summon Alba Zoa with Luluwalilith

 

Dogmatikamacabre x1 : You can search it with Herald of the Arc Light or Dogmatikamatrix , but we don’t use it in the combo. It is mainly used to summon White Relic or Alba Zoa form the GY ;

 

Dogmatika Punishment x1 : It is always nice to interrupt your opponent , and you can destroy/return to the hand/negate 1 extra card with N’tss/Malong/Aggregator

 

Extra deck monsters :

 

Albion the Sanctifire Dragon x1 : Summon it with Branded in Red , albaz and (most of the time) Ecclesia to Puppet lock your opponent and summon back cartesia (Note : You can puppet lock him AGAIN the next turn as long as puppet is in the GY and if you have remaining monster zones)

 

Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon x1 : You don’t use it often , it is mostly used when you can’t puppet lock your opponent

 

Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon x1 : An omni negate that you summon with duality and either Granguinol/Maximus/Fleurdelis (you mostly summon it with the remaining maximus on your field)

 

Granguignol the Dusk Dragon x1 : Summon it with Cartesia’s effect and Albaz (i’ve explained why Albaz before) to send Puppet to your GY

 

Titaniklad the Ash Dragon x1 : You mostly use it to search Albaz (if you don’t have it in your hand)

 

Albion the Branded Dragon x1 : You mostly use it to set Branded in Red form your deck (if you don’t have it in your hand)

 

Garura, Wings of Resonant Life x1 : It can be a target for nadir servant or to summon maximus , and draw 1 is nice !

 

Elder Entity N’tss x1 : A tool to destroy 1 card on the field

 

Despian Luluwalilith x1 : You gonna use to to summon Alba Zoa and summon Cartesia in the end phase

 

Golden Cloud Beast – Malong x1 : A tool to return to hand 1 card of your opponent

 

Herald of the arc Light x2 : Send it to the GY with Maximus to search either Dogmatikalamity/Alba Zoa

 

Mereologic Aggregator x1 : A tool to negate 1 card on the field

 

Secure Gardna x1 : Summon it to send almiraj to the GY (for maximus) and allow yourself to summon Ecclesia

 

Salamangreat Almiraj x1 : Summon it with Gen , turn it into Secure Gardna and banish it to summon Maximus

 

Side :

 

Dogmatika Nexus x1 : A nice board breaker

 

Tri-Brigade Arms Bucephalus II x1 : A target for Ultimate Slayer and allow us to draw 1 by sending Garura in the GY

 

Dark Ruler No More x3 : Negate everything to be safe

 

Ultimate Slayer x3 : Destroy 1 extra deck monster safely and contribute to the combo by sending your extra deck to the GY

 

Evenly matched x3 : A nice board breaker

4 more cards : Idk what i could add

 

The combo :

If we assume we have Ecclesia and Gen/Reinforcement of the Army , the combo should be :

Search Gen with Reinforcement of the Army (even if you have it , so you can bait ash) , Normal summon Gen , special summon Ken , use Triples Tactics card if you need it, summon almiraj then secure gardna , special summon Ecclesia , search Dogmatikamatrix , activate dogmatikamatrix , search Alba zoa/Dogmatikalamity and maximus , banish almiraj to summon maximus , use maximus effect to send to the GY Herald and either Titaniklad/Albion the Branded Dragon , Search with Herald Alba zoa/Dogmatikalamity , summon Alba Zoa with Dogmatikalamity and Luluwalilith , use Dogmatikamatrix to send Titaniklad/Albion the Branded Dragon to the GY , set Duality (if you have it) then End phase

 

At the end phase , you should have in your GY : Luluwalilith , Titaniklad and Albion the Branded Dragon (and more cards but those 3 are important) . On you field you should have : Alba Zoa , Ecclesia , Secure Gardna , Maximus , Dogmatikamatrix and (if you had it) duality face down

 

Use Luluwalilith to summon Cartesia , Titaniklad to search Albaz and Albion the Branded Dragon to set Branded in Red.

In the main phase of you opponent : Summon Granguinol with cartesia and Albaz , use it to send Puppet to the GY , target Albaz with Branded in Red and summon with Albaz and Ecclesia your Albion the Sanctifire Dragon to revive Puppet (on your opponent field) and Cartesia (on you field)

 

Congratulations , you have puppet locked your opponent !

 

The combo may change depending on your hand / opponents play , but you have a lot of choices

 

Thanks for reading , i hope you love the decklist , i’m personally proud of it !

 

Have a nice day and have fun with the deck !
Siu

deck_excerpt: My older ancient gear deck with the newer supports
deck_description: My older ancient gear deck with the newer supports
Fusion Spamming at its finest

This is a heavy combo deck which allows you to consistently setup an unbeatable board, especially when going first and still has OTK options even when going second. The combo will end you on: tripple card return, omni negate, spell + trap negate, every monster can't be targeted with card effects or attacked +  full Ibllee lock preventing summoning.

 

Main combo line (cyberse lock + iblee)

Req: have firewall defenser or a card that can give it (cynet mining, bitron). alternatively can be done with cynet codec + 2 monsters on field.

1) Summon firewall defenser

2) Link into Balelynx (ch1: defenser, ch2: baleynx) - to protect against ash

3) get sanctuary from Balelynx, summon firewall phantom 

4) Link phantom + baleynx => splash mage (use phantom effect to get cynet codec if you don't already have it, discarding sanctuary or another spell)

If you have cynet codec, get whichever spell you don't have and haven't used yet: Cynet mining/Cynet Optimization, Cynet Conflict, cynet storm

5) Use splash mage to summon defenser or any level 4 or below monster (dont summon back phantom)

6) link splash mage's material into link decoder

7) Activate Cynet Codec

8) splash mage + link decoder => transcode talker (TOP RIGHT EXTRA ZONE) (ch1: cynet codec, ch2: decoder)

9) From cynet codec get: code generator, gatchiri ignister. Depending on which one you don't have.

10) Summon decoder on the right most monster zone

11) transcode talker effect to summon splash mage below

12) splash mage + code generator from hand => excode talker. (ch1: codec, ch2: code gen in GY, ch3: excode talker)

13) from codec get: parallel exceed, link infra, code exporter. Depending on which one you don't have. Code gen in GY should discard Dotscapper. Excode talker needs to block the zone above transcode.

14) Trigger dotscapper from gy summon anywhere on the field.

15) dotscapper + transcode talker => code talker inverted on the left side of excode talker (ch1: inverted, ch2: cynet codec)

16) codec: get lady debug,  backup secretary. code talker inverted: summon lady debug on the left.

17) activate lady debug effect get: micro coder, ibllee, or another extender

18) micro coder from hand + inverted => protectcode talker (ch1: cynet codec, ch2: micro coder)

19) micro coder add spell in the same order from step 4 Depending on which one you don't have. Codec: get ibblee or a ritual monster if you already have her and have no rituals in hand.

20) If you haven't used cynet mining use it on ibblee, get extender that you can special summon: backup sec, infra, gatchiri, etc. If you already used cynet mining use cynet optimization and summon iblee on the field. and use her for the next link summon.

21) lady debug + link decoder OR lady debug + iblee => cyberse witch (TOP LEFT extra zone). Activate parallel exceed and summon it bellow witch.

(ch1: witch, ch2: exceed)

22) exceed: summon next to the other exceed. witch: banish any spell from GY (you should have one already) get cyberse magician.

21) Use witch effect to summon iblee on the last monster zone, or if you already have ibblee on opponent field.

22) cyberse witch + protectcode + parallel exceed below witch => firewall singularity in the middle.

23) check your hand. You should have a monster to special summon from cynet mining and hopefully another monster except degrade buster.

24)

  a) If you don't have other monster, summon protectcode from GY. Protectcode + ibllee => wicckid TOP LEFT EXTRA

  b) If you do link exceed + ibblee => wicckid TOP LEFT EXTRA

25) ibblee effect, summon her in the middle field of opponent.

26) Use your special summoning monster from hand to summon under wicckid => activate wicckid effect

27) get cyber sage from wicckid

28) ritual summon cyber sage below wicckid by using the monster from step 26. Don't activate singularity yet!

29) Cyber sage => summon Desavewurm => Desavewurm effect summon a monster from your hand, don't change it's level

30) Synchro sage + Desavewurm=> Quantum dragon below wicckid. (ch1: cyber sage effect, ch2: firewall singularity)

31) Singualrity: summon back splash mage, cyber sage: get back ritual spell from GY

32) Splash mage + random monster from step 29 => heatsoul top right. (ch1: cynet codec)

33) Get degrade buster from codec. Then use heatsoul to draw a card.

34) use ritual spell again to summon Cyberse magician on the right side of excode talker.

35) set down Cynet conflict if you have it.

36) Final field left to right: (Quantum dragon, singularity, excode talker, cyberse magician. TOP LEFT EXTRA: wicckid, TOP RIGHT EXTRA: heatsoul)

 

Active protections

 

Card effects and battle

Quantum dragon + Cyberse magician (Cyberse lock) - they both have an effect making it so that nobody can target other monsters with card effects or attack them creating a dupe lock. All of your monsters are now untargetable by card effects and attacks. Magician halfs card effect damage. Quantum dragon can return one monster it battles with.

Protection: wicckid protects quantum dragon, singualrity and itself from getting destroyed by card effects. Firewall defenser in GY also protects singualrity. Excode talker protects every other monster in the same way. Only Excode talker is vulnerable to non-targeting card destruction, like Dark hole. Singualrity can bring him back on the field during opponent's turn 1 time.

 

Interruptions:

Complete iblee lock: both extra zones are occupied and the zone above heatsoul is blocked by excode creating a full iblee lock. Your opponent cannot special summon monsters, before ibblee leaves the field.

Desave in GY negates against spell/trap effects. Cynet conflict is an omni negate. Singualrity can return up to 3 cards per turn as a Quick Effect.

 

There is also a second line that gets you to the same place by starting with lady debug when you don't have access to firewall defenser, but I won't add it to keep this smaller.

 

When going second you can just get to Darkfluid, go battle phase and attack the weakest face up monster. Activate darkfluid effect. Discard mathmech multiplication and multiply darkluid attack. This will one shot your opponent and they can't stop it except with traps/quickspells.

Weaknesses

You are vulnerable to every single handtrap in the game, but depending on your hand you may be able to get somewhere good.

If you get to setup your board, it is very hard for your opponent to do anything, but you can still lose to non-targeting banish or tribute summoning, with Kaijus for example.

 

Changes you can make

The deck doesn't have many handtraps and I am using card  destruction + left arm offering, because it plays very funny against Maxx-C.

Your deck summons a lot so if you get either of these cards in hand, just play through maxx-C, summon as much as you can and then use card destruction for an FTK XDDD.

You can remove these cards or cut the second combo line by removing lady debugs to 1, and micro coders to 1, to add more handtraps, but then you are risking being unable to do your combo so becareful!

 

Final remarks

If you go First, have Mainline requirement and they have no interruptions, you kinda just win the game.

Abyss Actor is a Pendulum deck based on performing arts, and focused on maintaining card advantage and making the opponent destroy their own Set cards. The deck has very accessible 1-card combos with  Abyss Actor - Extras, ending on a monster effect redirection with Abyss Playhouse - Fantastic Theater and protection with Abyss Actor - Sassy Rookie. Lava Golem and Lightning Storm are here to help clear boards for an OTK. This list also plays D/D/D Vice King Requiem to allow you to make D/D/D Vice King Requiem as another piece of interruption, while staying inexpensive. I would recommend this deck for more experienced players, as newer and returning players can be sometimes be confused by the Pendulum mechanic.

Altergeist is a midrange deck based on female mythical creatures with names based on computing terminology, and focused on Link Summoning and Trap Cards. Altergeist do not have a way to execute their full combo with 1 card, but have plenty of 2-card combos. The typical endboard, if you open Altergeist Marionetter and Altergeist Meluseek, consists of 2 negates, access to a bounce on the opponent's turn, a reborn and a steal. If you only open Altergeist Meluseek though, you can still end on Herald of the Arc Light. The deck has quite a lot of room for non-engine, so I've opted for handtraps, Rivalry of Warlords and Secret Village of the Spellcasters. The handtraps give you the option to interact with your opponent if they go first and the floodgates are, well, floodgates. I'd recommend Altergeist to players that enjoy versatile decks.
Crazy end-board, and lots of interruptions

D/D/D is a Pendulum deck based on Western history, and focused on Special Summoning and taking effect damage. D/D/D's combos are extremely varied, to the point where the deck is affectionately known as "the spreadsheet deck", due to there being a spreadsheet featuring multiple combos using 1 card, 2 cards and 3 cards. Quite often, the deck ends on a twice-per-turn Special Summon negate and at least monster attaches via D/D/D Deviser King Deus Machinex. Depending on your hand, you can also end on a negate that steals, a Spell/Trap negate, a way to lock your opponent out of Extra Deck summons and/or targeting protection for your monsters. I'd recommend D/D/D to experienced players that are looking for a challenge.

I dont really know what Im doing here to be honest, I just wanted to take a stab at some banter deck that I saw on the internet. Ik it may not be the most efficient, with any luck this deck will be made more efficient as I find cards to replace other cards or understand the deck to a higher degree. lol
A 100% normal Snake-Eyes deck that doesn't have anything suspicious about it at all.

Switched from Flame Swordsman/Red-Eyes, to more of a pure Flame Swordsman deck. Although I'm not playing it anymore, I'm keeping the other deck profile up and making this new one. There is a lot of space for hand traps in this deck which is really great.

One thing thats kind of nice, is that if you don't open any of your 1 card combos, and you open Fusion Armament with Bradamante, you can still Fuse into Ultimate Flame Swordsman or Fighting Flame Dragon.

By the time I had finished the main deck, I realized that I had a lot of tuners, so I tried to throw in some random Fire Synchro monsters in that are relatively easy to summon. Black Rose can either be summoned off of Ash plus Flame Swordsman, or Roland plus Salamandra. Ruddy can be summoned off of either Gearfried plus any of the 1 star tuners, or Black Rose, plus Ash. Roland can be summoned off of Flame Swordsman plus any 1 star, or Salamandra plus Ash. Could also cut 1 of each Flame Swordsman Fusion monster for 2 more link monsters potentially. Maybe a Knightmare Phoenix, or another generic fire link monster like Pitknight Earlie or one of the Salamangreat link monsters, or even I:P.

Promethean is great. Also running only Fire types in the extra deck so you never get locked out of any special summoning, aside from Nibiru in the side deck. Could run any other 3 instead of Nibiru, because there are quite a few ways to break your opponent's board, I just chose Nibiru because I couldn't think of another side option. Maybe could try Fire Recovery? Not sure.

Majespecter is a midrange Pendulum deck based on Asian mythology and focuses on generating card advantage and Tributing WIND Spellcaster monsters to activate effects. The deck has a few 1-card combos, which end on at least a twice-per-turn Special Summon from your deck, Secret Village of the Spellcasters and either a Solemn Strike-esque Counter Trap or a monster banish. The deck can play 9-15 handtraps, but this build opts for 9 in order to run Wynn the Wind Channeler, as it can search Majespecter Crow - Yata if you don't open it. I'd recommend this deck to players that want to learn the fundamentals of a Pendulum deck.

Orcust is a DARK deck based on orchestral music and focuses on Link Summoning and banishing Machine monsters. The deck's 1-card combos involve sending Orcust Harp Horror from the Deck to the Graveyard, ending on at least an omni-negate Counter Trap, and usually either I:P Masquerena or Evilswarm Nightmare as well. The deck has a load of space for non-engine, and I've opted for 12 handtraps and a Small World package, though this can be replaced with more handtraps. I'd recommend this deck to players that want to throw a harp into the bin.

deck_excerpt: Zombie World ft. Paladin of the Cursed Dragon & Honest
deck_description:
Zombie World deck using Paladin of the Cursed Dragon ft. Thunder King Rai-Oh and Honest.

* Deck has a ton of synergy if you can get the field spell to stick. Paladin can steal opponent's monsters, very useful if you Creature Swap your Goblin or Turtle to the enemy's side and attack into it with Paladin, getting your special summon and Goblin/Turtle back.
* Thunder King is fantastic with Zombie World up, able to negate any special summons then be brought back/reused with Book of Life/Zombie Master/Mezuki to keep your opponent out of Special Summons.
* Honest and Chalice are great combat tricks with Paladin or Thunder King, even if Paladin's effect gets negated, it isn't turn specific, so if you use Chalice during your opponent's turn, once it gets back to your turn his effect will return and you can use it to grab whatever was destroyed during combat.
* Book of Moon helps Paladin get over more things and can also be useful with Doomkaiser as flipping the monster you stole face down will remove the destruction effect.
* Summoner Monk can use extra spell cards like Terra/Zombie World (or non-live Book) to bring out key cards.

________

Still testing cards, Side deck certainly isn't optimized/is just housing a few cards I'd like to try.

Marionette Mite is a cool card once Zombie World is up, however struggled to find deck space for it and not enough cards to convert off it (e.g. would need more tuners, tributes or sac outlets to make use of the stolen card before the end of turn). If I did find space though, it would also open up access to Underground Arachnid which I might consider, as it's a very strong card.
Card Guard can be a useful summon of Summoner Monk, allowing you to protect your Zombie World (or a monster/synchro) you don't want destroyed, otherwise Field Barrier is good against other decks that run Field Spells.
Rivalry can be a fun side in card, if Zombie World is up and they control a monster on field, basically locks them down, unable to summon anything else (barring the mirror).
Imperial Iron Wall is handy against GY hate, but also a really fun mini-engine with Plaguespreader.
There's also the idea of running Everliving Underworld Cannon as each steal/special summon would cause a considerable amount of burn damage, but might be a little too gimmicky/not enough space.
I'd like to find room for a single Gale, great effect that synergises with out gameplan, gives us another Tuner and opens up the extra deck to some Blackwing Synchro's.
Would love Threatening Roar in the main deck to help against speedier decks, but again, deck space.
Finally, Caius sure would be nice. But yeah, not sure where I'd fit him.
The deck I use

deck_excerpt: OTK with Tenpai and FTK with Centur-Ion! FREE CHEESY EZ WINS!
deck_description:
Have you tried "asking your friends" for a copy of Trident Dragion (good joke btw Komoney lmao)? Or did you randomly have the guy in your bulk from 2009? Well you're in luck, since Tenpai Dragons have made this card extremely powerful and competitively viable! 
 
For the "year of fire's" finale and acknowledgement of the "year of the Dragion" for the Chinese New Year, Konami has really outdid themselves this time.  Through a field full of monsters, hand full of handtraps, gamestate with plentiful interruption, Tenpai Dragons can still obliterate all your opponent's lifepoints EASYYYY! 
 
One turn kill your opponent with the force of a million suns with the combined absurdly high attack power of Tenpai - up to 36400 total lifepoint damage! Not only are these dragons unaffected during Main Phase 1 through their archetypal field spell, these cards are so consistent with 16 1-card starters that you can jam about 25 staples into the deck! You can inundate your opponent with a flurry of handtraps and boardbreakers then proceed to their final reckoning as you go to your battle phase.
 
My personal twist to Tenpai is the "smokescreen" and "bait n' switch" mindgames I play with the Side Deck - the entire sidedeck is the Centur-Ion core. The fiendishly cunning strategy first blind-second OTKs your opponent with Tenpai, then you side in your entire Centur-Ion Side Deck to "Calamity Lock" FTK when your opponent forces you to go first! 
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 

ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING 

 

Not mixed with any other archetypes, Tenpai Dragon is usually played "pure." This deck has so many staples in it while being consistent that duelists sometimes say the Tenpai player is using a OTK engine in a handtrap deck!

 

The TENPAI cards are a potent, compact and consistent OTK strategy composed primarily of 1-card starters. Almost every Tenpai card has as much potential and gas as "Branded Fusion" and "Snake-Eyes Ash!" This deck core uses 3 Sangen Summoning (searcher field spell), 3 Sangen Kaimen (emergency teleport), 3 Tenpai Chundra (summons from deck), 3 Tenpai Paidra (spell/trap searcher) and 2 Fadra (quick efffect synchro summon - the only non-starter). Terraforming and Pot of Prosperity count as additional 1 card starters, effectively granting this deck 16 1-card starters. 

 

The funny twist with this strategy is that the Side Deck is composed entirely of CENTUR-ION cards. These 15 cards in the Side Deck give you incredibly consistent access to a Calamity Lock, essentially giving you 16 1-card starters just like Tenpai. The 3 Primera, 3 Trudea, 3 Stand-Up, and 3 Emblema Oath combined with the Main Deck's Terraforming and Pot of Prosperity allow this deck incredible access to it's strategy. 

 

The rest of the deck are STAPLES! The board breakers consist of x3 Kashtira Fenrir, x2 Droplet x2 Lightning Storm and x1 Harpie's Feather Duster. These board breakers disproportionately eliminate your opponent's resources to make a breakthrough and OTK with Tenpai much easier. There are handtraps aplenty in this deck - so much so that your opponent will most likely have a sub-optimal board facing down your OTK juggernaut. 

 

COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN 

 

The GAMEPLAN with this deck is straightforward – Slowdown your opponent with handtraps, break their board with boardbreakers, then OTK/FTK with your many 1-card starters!

 

You'll always win the die-roll since you want to go second. Here is the main going-second COMBO for Tenpai Dragon:

 

Sangen Summoning + Discard = 30000+ damage!

 

  1. Activate Sangen Summoning.
  2. Use Sangen Summoning's effect to search Paidra from deck. Discard a card. 
  3. Normal summon Paidra. Search Sangen Kaimen from deck. 
  4. Enter the Battle Phase. Activate Sangen Kaimen to add Chundra from deck to hand then summon it. 
  5. Attack with Chundra. At the start of the damage step, summon Fadra from deck. 
  6. Attack with as many monsters as possible (make at least 3 attacks so that your Extra Deck Tenpai's effects are live).
  7. Activate Chundra's quick synchro effect to synchro summon Sangenpai Bident Dragion using Chundra + Fadra. 
  8. Sangenpai Bident Dragon's on-summon effect to summon from GY Fadra. 
  9. Activate Fadra's effect to summon Chundra from GY. Attack with as many monsters as possible.
  10. Activate Fadra's effect to quick synchro into Trident Dragion using Bident Dragion + Fadra. 
  11. Activate Trident Dragion's on-summon effect to destroy Sangen Summoning and another card you control so it can make 3 attacks.
  12. Activate Sangen Summon's trigger effect in the GY targeting Trident Dragion to double it's attack. 
  13. Attack three times with a 6000 ATK Trident Dragion! As needed, you can summon Bident Dragion from GY to destroy a spell/trap and for additional damage.
 
Obviously, this deck can deviate from the above combo to fit the situation as needed. For example, can use Rose Dragon + Sangen Summoning to destroy everything on the field to clear your opponent's board, then proceed to OTK in the battle phase with your singular Sangen Kaimen. You can also access your synchro toolbox like Samuri Destroyer or Quantum Dragon to counter specific hard to out threats like Yubel or rival Tenpai duelists. 
 
If you haven't finished off your opponent yet, you can link off your remaining Dragons to Hieratic Seals or S:P Little Knight, which are both powerful monsters in a simplified gamestate. Next turn, you can attempt to OTK again! 
 
Congrats duelist, you've cheesed your way to a win/loss in the first match. You've mentally imprinted into your opponent's brain that you are a stinky dirty blind second player who wants to go second. Now more likely than not, your opponent will force you to go first. Your opponent may have sided in anti-Tenpai cards like One Day of Peace and taken out their handtraps like Nibiru.
 
To hardcounter and metagame your opponent's predicted mentality, we "cheese" them with some super secret tactics! Time to take out all your Tenpai cards, bring in your entire Centur-Ion Side Deck and Calamity lock! Take out the 14 Tenpai cards and 1 Lightning Storm and side in our 15 Centur-Ion cards.
 
Your opponent will likely force you to go first after experiencing your Tenpai onslaught. Here is the Centur-Ion 1-card COMBO:
 
Primera/Trudea/Stand-Up/Emblema Oath = Legatia (Pop highest ATK monster, draw 1 and resource generator) + Calamity Lock (Or omni-negate with Blazar Dragon) + follow-up
 
  1. Normal summon Primera to search Stand-Up!
  2. Activate Stand-Up! Use Stand-Up's effect to send 1 card from hand to GY to place Trudea on the backrow as a continuous trap.
  3. Special summon Trudea from the backrow.
  4. Activate Trudea's effect to place itself on the backrow and Gargoyle II from deck on the backrow.
  5. Special summon Gargoyle II from the backrow.
  6. Synchro summon Legatia using Primera + Gargoyle II.
  7. Activate Legatia's on-summon effect to pop a monster with highest ATK your opponent controls (if applicable) and draw 1 card.
  8. During the End Phase, activate Legatia's effect to place Primera on the backrow as a continuous trap.
  9. During the opponent's Main Phase, special summon Primera (CL1) and Trudea as a level 8 (CL2) from the backrow.
  10. CL1 Primera to search a Centur-Ion card (usually Bonds since it's excellent follow-up), and CL2 Stand-Up to synchro summon using Primera + Trudea for Crimson Dragon.
  11. Activate Crimson Dragon targeting Legatia to synchro summon King Calamity from Extra Deck. (If your opponent interrupts Crimson Dragon so that King Calamity loses it's timing window to resolve it's on-summon effect, summon Supernova Dragon instead). Activate King Calamity to prevent your opponent from activating any cards on the field. 
 
You can also opt to summon Auxilia instead of Legatia if you've excavated with Pot of Prosperity so you can search instead of draw. Auxilia has the added bonus of protecting your backrow, so they can't be Ghost Ogre'd (common handtrap nowadays) to death. Auxilia allows you to place a Centur-Ion into your backrow from Banishment, so it can play through Dimension Shifter. Auxilia is a safer play, while Legatia is a slightly greedier play with it's draw 1. 

 

GENERAL TIPS

  • Since this deck contains a ton of handtraps, remember to handtrap your opponents at the most opportune time! Knowing when and where to handtrap is essential to this deck's success since a weakened opponent vastly increases your chances of OTK or FTK. Be sure to study up! 
  • If you can't finish off your opponent with your first OTK attempt with Tenpai, make Seals/S:P with your remaining monsters and maintain your handtraps. You'll likely place your opponent in a simplified gamestate after your onslaught. So a single/couple interruptions is enough to slow them down so you can OTK them again next turn! 
  • Sometimes in games 2/3, your opponent may still go first (perhaps they think you'll use Heatwave or some other kind of floodgate). Worry not! Your Centur-Ion deck has 25 staples/handtraps/boardbreakers to slow down your opponent so you can still play a regular grindgame with their simplified gamestate with the Centur-Ion cards. The only problem 
  • The "bait n' switch" and "smokescreening" of this strategy requires a lot of mindgames with your opponent. You have to predict your opponent's mentality and confidence to determine if you think they'll force you to go 1st. 
  • While not optimal, both Tenpai and Centur-Ion can achieve their goals under Dimension Shifter. 
  • If you're worried about the price of Trident Dragion's hefty $120 price tag, it is not mandatory for the Tenpai strategy. You may not be able to OTK through Prosperity and Shifter however. 9 times out of 10 however, from personal experience I find that games finish with Tenpai before Trident Dragion comes out. 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 

CONCLUDING REMARKS

 
This strategy has won me quite a few cheesy quick matches in online duels and in real life Locals. My opponents were often dumbfounded and caught unawares by the strategy, since their sided anti-Tenpai cards had little to no effect on Centur-Ion! They often tell you to go 1st, leaving them wholly vulnerable to a full Calamity lock combo! "Bait n' switch" and "smokescreening" are now back with a vengeance in 2024 with Centur-Ion as players pretend to play one strategy only to blindside their opponent with 36400 DAMAGE from Tenpai or a Calamity lock from Centur-Ion! I personally had hilariously short rounds at Locals as I'd blaze through my opponents with your surprise tactics. 
 
Players are sure to catch on to this "cheesy" style of dueling so it's competitive viability might not be around for long. In the meantime while folks are blissfully unaware... Lets enjoy our free wins! 😉 
 

GLHF Duelists!

My Slifer Numeron deck profile. Slifer is my favorite nostalgia card. He's super easy to summon in this deck. Numeron is super budget and puts a lot of bodies on board to tribute to Slifer. If you don't have Slifer though, your Numeron monsters can win you the game anyway.

I put a bunch of board breakers into the side deck, like Nibiru, Thunderforce, Cyber Jar, and Mirror Force. Mirror Force and Infinite Impermanence work well with Trap Trick so I went with those as side deck options instead of other hand traps. Cyber Jar is great because it's a board wipe/draw 5 that can also put a couple of extra bodies onto the board if you draw into your non-Slifer monsters. 

You can probably cut 1 each of Numeron Calling, Planet Pathfinder, and Numeron Wall for 3 of the side deck options, as drawing more than 1 of any of them feels bad. Then maybe swap in some other hand traps into the side deck. This is what I stuck with though.

deck_excerpt: Updated after some much needed testing and adjustments.
deck_description:
After some testing, I have figured out that actually playing Z-arc is worth the lack of extra deck space. This list is much more streamlined into getting access to you're mainline combo whether or not you have access to ositnato. 

Obviously this deck can still put up a formidable endboard with ostinato ending on vortex, masq, Exceed the pend, and a live Soul of the Supreme celestial king that translates into a Z-arc pop. I wont go over everything i did in the last list(just go look at that for the main stuff.) So for this I will just explain some more specific details.

1.Z-arc is worth it to play around some specifics. The original lists endboard was countered by DRNM but now you can retain access to a board wipe with the trap. Plus I have noticed that Tenpai has some serious issues getting around Z-arc conventionally.

2. This builds ED space is extremly tight. You have basically 2 free spots to use for tech. I choose Underworld Goddess to deal with potential Towers and I choose tapier in awkward hands that can only put 2 bodies but no scales on board. Everything els is, imo, Mandatory. 

3. The reason for the Odd-eyes pend dragon is cause its material for Z-arc. You need to banish Dragons specifically off the trap to get Z-arc online so using the pend magicians that are always treated as each dragon doesnt work. And because the ED space is tight having 1 of the dragons maindecked gives some space to work.

4. Realistically it doesnt matter if you go with the original or the Normal Pendulum dragon, both are just material for Z-arc. The only notable differences are that Pendulum dragon can search out Gate Zero, Couplet, or Luisworm in VERY awkward hands whereas Arc Pend Dragon can be foolished for dragon shrine to still send Druisworm and has favorable High scale. They aren't bricks per say but that doesnt mean its fun to draw them. 

5. This deck can realistically play through most handtraps. D-shifter is where Baguska comes in since most decks on shifter have problems with the sleepy boi. Nibiru can be annoying but opponents will have to fire it early to prevent you from getting your vortex dragon online, Usually you will still have the Pendulum summon left after they nib early. You dont have to search AS much if you get drolled but obviously you will have a weaker endboard but it will still be a competent endboard. 

If you have questions or comments, let me know below.

Pretty much, this deck uses the Starry Knight archetype's loop to outsource opponents by popping cards on field, banishing themselves from grave for extra bodies/drawing and recursion with Bystials/Runick. The strategy is still pretty one-note, but they have access to Colossus with their banished assets being shuffled with Nemeses. Magnamut can search for either more Bystials or the Starry Dragon itself if need be. Any Bystial + Fairy Knight is a free Chaos Angel. Zeus is pretty much a last resort if you can't keep field advantage. Starring knight is a great loop extender for the Dragon allowing a special summon without using the baackrow and also being able to act as Bystial fodder in grave or specialing back out to pitch specific Knights in the grave for their own banishing effects, manage them wisely.

deck_excerpt: Snake-Eye, except augmented with several Kashtira cards. Arguably the optimal way to play the deck!
deck_description:
This is Snake-Eye, except it is augmented with the several Kashtira cards granting the strategy additional free-to-summon bodies, extension, board-breaking capability, and even an Extra Deck rip. Before Fire Kings come out in Masterduel, Kashtira is most likely the best combination to play with Diabellstar and friends. This is my deck of choice to play Masterduel ladder right now since it can go either first or second, plays a ton of handtraps and staples, extremely consistent, while being reliably powerful!

Diabellestar, Snake-Eyes and it's variants are so dominant on Masterduel ladder and tournaments that the deck is considered "tier 1!" Wield the power of a tier 1 deck to win every game to get that coveted Masters 1 rank! Snake-Eyes is definitely the deck to achieve Masters 1 this format since it's so ridiculously powerful and consistent with Bonfire. This is the deck I reached Masters 1 with this season, and you definitely can as well!

If you want a detailed guide on how to play this deck, check out my earlier article by clicking here.

If you have any questions about this deck, feel free to ask me in the comments below!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

deck_excerpt: Tenpai Dragon  / Nicaragua National Championships 1st Place
deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Dexter Sequeira

Tournament: Nicaragua National Championships – May 5th 2024

Placement: 1st Place

La estrategia del Tenpai se centra en el uso de monstruos Dragón Tenpai, como Pedra y Chundra, que te permiten buscar cartas de hechizo/trampa Sangen. Las cartas Sangen, como Sangen Kiman y Sangen Summoning, son cruciales para proteger e invocar monstruos de forma especial. El mazo también incluye cartas de coherencia como Pot of Prosperity, Set Rotation y Terraforming. Además, hay "Rompe campos" como Harpy's Feather Duster, Lightning Storm y Forbidden Droplet, así como trampas de mano como Ash Blossom, Ghost Belle e Impermanence para interrumpir.

 

El Extra deck incluye Synchros como Sangan Pai Bident Dragon, Trishula y Black Rose Dragon.

 

El objetivo de este mazo es establecer un campo fuerte con cartas Tenpai Dragons y Sangen, proteger a tus monstruos con trampas de mano e interrumpir las jugadas de tu oponente con cartas de destrucción de campo. Luego, usa tus monstruos Synchro para abrumar a tu oponente y asegurar la victoria.

 

Combo para el primer turno:

 

Dos Dragones Tenpai: Invoca normalmente una copia de Blanco, usa su efecto para agregar una carta de Hechizo del mazo a tu mano. Invoca de forma especial a Rojo, controlando un monstruo Dragón de Fuego. Usa Blanco y Rojo como materiales de Link para invocar Esferas del Dragón de Hielo. Esto te permite hacer rebotar una carta en el campo a la mano durante el turno de tu oponente y convocar a un Dragón del mazo usando el efecto de Esferas en el cementerio.

Sangen spell, Verde + 1: activa Sangen para agregar Blanco del mazo a tu mano. Invoca normalmente a Blanco, usa su efecto para agregar el hechizo con nombre diferente del mazo a tu mano. Activa el hechizo para agregar Rojo del mazo a tu mano. Activa Rojo para convocarlo de forma especial al campo. Usa Blanco y Rojo para convocar por sincronización al Dragón Hada Antiguo. Usa el efecto del Dragón Hada Antiguo para convocar de forma especial a un monstruo de nivel 4 o inferior desde tu mano (Verde), luego usa su efecto para agregar campo. Usa Ancient Fairy Dragon y Rojo para convocar en sincronización a Shooting Star Dragon. Coloca Secret Village of the Spellcasters desde tu mano. Con el efecto de Shooting Star Dragon, manda tenpai Rojo y sincroniza con Ancient Fairy Dragon para invocar Nirvana High Paladin.

Combo para el segundo turno:

Dimension Shifter OTK: activa Dimension Shifter en el turno de tu oponente. Usa Sangan Kimman para agregar Rojo o Blanco. Ataca con Rojo y Blanco, luego usa el efecto de Rojo para convocar verde, luego ocupa el efecto de Blanco para convocar por sincronización a Senpai Bident Dragon y ataca. Realiza una sincronización rápida con Verde y Senpai Bident Dragon para convocar a Trident Dron. Usa el efecto de Trident Dron para destruir el hechizo de campo boca abajo, duplicar su ataque y obtener un ataque adicional. Ataca dos veces para causar 6000 de daño cada uno.

 

Black Rose Dragon Board Breaker: Invoca normalmente a Blanco, usa su efecto para agregar a Kimman del mazo a tu mano. convoca de forma especial a Rojo desde el mazo, ataca y usa el efecto de Rojo para convocar Verde. Activa el efecto para Invocar por sincronización a Black Rose Dragon, destruyendo todas las cartas en el campo, incluida tu invocación Sangan. Activa Kimman para invocar Verde y renacer Rojo. Ataca directamente con Verde, Rojo, realiza Sincronización para Sangen y renace Black Rose Dragon.

Estos combos te ayudarán a maximizar el potencial de Tenpai Dragon tanto en el primer como en el segundo turno, permitiéndote romper tableros, OTK y controlar el juego. Recuerda adaptar estos combos según la situación y las cartas que tengas en la mano.

deck_excerpt: To scoop or not to scoop.....
deck_description:
Hello! This is my ideal way to run vaalmonica post LEDE. 

I found that although this variant doesn't have a huge turn 1, it can quickly, and consistently gain massive advantage on turn 3 and over.

Since the vaalmonica engine doesn't really need its normal summon, the invoked engine feels pretty good and it provides you with an omni negate + a discard for your pendelum monsters to scale themselves.

A typical combo with Magical Meltdown + a Vaalmonica scale and a spell would go: Magical Meltdown -> Normal Summon Alister -> add invocation -> Link into Artemis -> Fusion Summon Mechaba -> Add back the Alister -> Activate one of the vaalmonica pendelums discarding Alister (Ideally you want to discard Selettrice to add itself back or a trap to use the effect from the graveyard via Zebufera later) -> Set scales (At this point in the combo you want a Selettrice in your hand so you can go through your vaalmonica spells, the main ways to do this are the field spell, invitare or drawing it. Note: Invitare locks you into vaalmonica monster effects so if you have it, use it after you link off Alister so that you can still get to Mechaba. You can also link off the Artemis + Selettrice into I:P Maquerena if you've set your scales already) After you set the scales, pend summon selettrice to get the effect and add vaalmonica scelta -> scelta effect using the take damage effect to grab disarmonia -> disarmonia effect adding back scelta (by now you have 3 resonance counters on dimmono so you can make zebufera -> Link off selettrice to summon zebuferra, set any traps and pass. With this you'll end on selettrice + scelta in hand, mechaba with a free monster negate via selettrice, zebufera to protect your cards and use spell effects in grave, and whatever else was in your opening hand. The following turn you should easily be able to get your field spell + 3 resonance counters on angello to make duralume which pops 3 monsters and can attack 3 times. If you get the 3rd counter while the field spell is on the board, you can steal an opponents monster. By this point you can do basically anything.

Non engine can be whatever you want, i went with some standard cards. 

The second invocation can be cut. 

For budget options, replace some of the sidedeck with alternatives like pankratops and wait for rarity collection 2 to reprint accesscode talker and apollousa. 

S:P can obviously replace the knightmares if you're balling like that. This also gives you room to add more invoked fusions, links or rank 4s.

Overall, the deck isn't spectacular and can't accomplish a lot turn 1 but it has a fun gimmick that can work well at against other rogue decks. And if you're lucky, your opponent wont read your cards.

Side Deck Not Included. 

Destiny HEROs (May 2024 Revamp)

Original (November 2022): https://ygoprodeck.com/deck/destiny-heros-449919 

This build is based off of the original, but instead of being a video deck list it is my modified version post-banlist that also includes a card that I thought would be cool and decent (Break The Destiny)

deck_excerpt: Zombie World ft. Paladin of the Cursed Dragon & Honest
deck_description:
Zombie World deck using Paladin of the Cursed Dragon ft. Thunder King Rai-Oh and Honest.

* Deck has a ton of synergy if you can get the field spell to stick. Paladin can steal opponent's monsters, very useful if you Creature Swap your Goblin or Turtle to the enemy's side and attack into it with Paladin, getting your special summon and Goblin/Turtle back.
* Thunder King is fantastic with Zombie World up, able to negate any special summons then be brought back/reused with Book of Life/Zombie Master/Mezuki to keep your opponent out of Special Summons.
* In the same vain, you can bring back Honest with Book/Master then return it to hand with it's effect to reuse again and again.
* Honest and Chalice are great combat tricks with Paladin or Thunder King, even if Paladin's effect gets negated, it isn't turn specific, so if you use Chalice during your opponent's turn, once it gets back to your turn his effect will return and you can use it to grab whatever was destroyed during combat.
* Book of Moon helps Paladin get over more things and can also be useful with Doomkaiser as flipping the monster you stole face down will remove the destruction effect. (You can also use Chalice to negate Doomkaisers effect on destruction allowing you to keep the stolen monster).
* Summoner Monk can use extra spell cards like Terra/Zombie World (or non-live Books) to bring out key cards.

________

Still testing cards, Side deck certainly isn't optimized/is just housing a few cards I'd like to try.

Marionette Mite is a cool card once Zombie World is up, however struggled to find deck space for it and not enough cards to convert off it (e.g. would need more tuners, tributes or sac outlets to make use of the stolen card before the end of turn). If I did find space though, it would also open up access to Underground Arachnid which I might consider, as it's a very strong card.
Card Guard can be a useful summon of Summoner Monk, allowing you to protect your Zombie World (or a monster/synchro) you don't want destroyed, otherwise Field Barrier is good against other decks that run Field Spells.
Rivalry can be a fun side in card, if Zombie World is up and they control a monster on field, basically locks them down, unable to summon anything else (barring the mirror).
Imperial Iron Wall is handy against GY hate, but also a really fun mini-engine with Plaguespreader.
There's also the idea of running Everliving Underworld Cannon as each steal/special summon would cause a considerable amount of burn damage, but might be a little too gimmicky/not enough space.
It's a LOT worse, but could always swap out Caius for Zaborg for another Honest target.
Would love to find Threatening Roar in the main deck to help against speedier decks, but again, deck space.
Finally, Trap Dustshoot would be nice, powerful disruption card and can put key cards in the GY for Doomkaiser to steal later on.

deck_excerpt: Nightmare Apprentice? Diabellze? Kitt? Chimera Branded is now a waifu deck.
deck_description:
With Legacy of Destruction, the entire Illusion archetype has received it's universal searcher - Nightmare Apprentice! Relatively free to summon extender that searches any Illusion monster from deck is a gigantic buff to the Chimera strategy. She also is an enabler for Chaos Angel in Chimera with the perfect attribute, dark - lining up with Mirror Swordsknight's light to make an unaffected towers Chaos Angel! 
 
Legacy of Destruction also bestows a honourary guest to the Chimera strategy - Diabellze. She is a mini "Anti-Spell" floodgate on legs, and now she's searchable and summonable with Chimera!

These two vixens grant Chimera a respectable boost in power - perhaps allowing the deck to compete with other tier 1 threats like Snake-Eye, Voiceless Voice and Tenpai. In addition to the immense card advantage, relentless fusion summons and giant boss monsters - Chimera now has a massive consistency buff and a backrow floodgate! 
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
As the name implies, Branded Chimera is composed of the two archetypes. One smaller support archetype is also utilized. Within two compact fusion engines lies a plethora of powerful plays that are highly searchable 1 card combos!
 
CHIMERA is fusion oriented deck core capable of overwhelming your opponent with sheer resources! For example, one Mirror Swordknight is a whopping +7 in card advantage! Chimera  is a simple and solid gameplan in itself with it's boss monsters - Chimera the King of Phantom Beasts and Berfomet the Mythical King of Phantom Beasts. While they are on the field, their names are "Chimera the Flying Mythical Beast." In the GY, Mirror Swordknight and Cornfield Coatl (sent to the GY as part of the combo) offer some targeting protection (Coatl) and monster effect negation (Swordknight). Berfomet and Gazelle nab resources from deck when summoned and used as fusion material. The deck's fusion card, Chimera Fusion, recurs itself from the GY if Chimera the Flying Mythical Beast is on the field or GY (which is always the case). Everything in this archetype grabs resources and recurs itself in this deck so you can keep fusion summoning and interrupting your opponent!
 
BRANDED in this strategy isn't the main focus - it is merely a support engine designed to increase the consistency and power of the Chimera cards. Branded Fusion is primarily used to fuse into Rindbrumm using Albaz and Gazelle the King of Mythical Claws, netting you an Illusion monster from deck. This starts your Chimera combo! A mini Despia engine is included with 3 Branded Opening, and 2 Aluber for a total of 8 direct ways to access Branded Fusion. Thrust can also fetch Branded Fusion from deck in certain gamestates. If you already have access to your Illusion cards, you can use Branded Fusion to go into the usual Branded Fusion combo lines to set up Mirrorjade or Dragoon.
 
The FRIGHTFUR cards are a mini package in this deck to further enable fusion plays and to assist with card advantage. The strategy needs ample amounts of resources in hand for discard fodder and fusion material, and the package provides ample resources specifically for those uses. 
 
This deck opts to play boardbreakers since it lacks space for mass handtraps. The boardbreaker line up are 3 Talents, 3 Thrust, 3 Droplet and 1 Evenly. Thrust also has an added bonus to search a starter like Branded Fusion. 
 
50 cards are used in this deck since the starters for both decks are highly searchable and are 1-card combos. 50 cards also makes it less likely that the garnets like Albaz, Gazelle and Berfomet are hard drawn. 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
Branded Chimera's usual strategy is deploying multiple fusion boss monsters backed by a robust gameplan and grindgame. Post Legacy of Destruction, the deck also sets up Diabellze to limit your opponent's spell/trap plays.

Here are Branded Chimera's main combos: 

You may notice in the side deck there are various fiend and fiend floodgates. End of Anubis shuts down decks like Snake-Eye and Tearlaments. Barrier Statue of the Abyss destroys strategies like Tenpai and Fire Kings. The newly available Diabellze renders spell/trap stratgies like Runick near unplayable. Now with a singular Mirror Swordknight or Nightmare Apprentice, these floodgates are easily searchable and summonable! 
 
Mirror Swordknight = Floodgate of choice (Lets use Diabellze for this example) + a lot of resources/follow-up + Berfomet the Mythical King of Phantom Beasts + 1 hand-rip + monster negate (Swordknight in GY) + targeting protection (Cornfield Coatl in GY). 
  1. Normal summon Mirror Swordknight. 
  2. Activate Mirror Swordknight's effect to summon Big-Winged Berfomet from deck.
  3. On summon, Big-Winged Berfomet searches for Chimera Fusion and Gazelle the King of Mythical Claws. 
  4. Activate Chimera Fusion to fusion summon Chimera the King of Phantom Beasts using Big-Winged Berfomet + Gazelle the King of Mythical Claws. 
  5. CL1 Big-Winged Berfomet to summon from GY Mirror Swordknight, CL2 Gazelle the King of Mythical Claws to search from deck any Illusion monster, CL3 Chimera the King of Phantom Beasts to send a random card from opponent's hand to the GY in the End Phase. 
  6. Activate Chimera Fusion in the GY to add it to your hand. 
  7. Activate Chimera Fusion to fusion summon Berfomet the Mythical King of Phantom Beasts by fusing Chimera the King of Phantom Beasts + any Beast, Fiend or Illusion. 
  8. On summon, Berfomet the Mythical King of Phantom Beasts sends to GY your target of choice (for this example let's use Diabellze). 
  9. During your end phase, resolve Chimera the King of Phantom Beasts' effect to send 1 random card for your opponent's hand to the GY.
  10. During your opponent's draw phase (or whenever you feel like it's best), activate Chimera the King of Phantom Beasts' effect to summon Diabellze from the GY. Master Tao the Chanter is also an alternate way to summon Diabellze from the GY. Just send to GY Tao with Berfomet and use Tao's GY effect to summon Diabellze!
Congrats! With a singular card you've locked your opponent out from playing spells/traps! This deck has a variety of searchable floodgates - use them depending on your match-up. 
 
The next combo involves Branded Fusion and with siding in a lingering floodgate, D/D Orthros. (This strategy can be maindecked, but this is better going 1st).
 
Mirror Swordknight + Branded Fusion = fiend-lock for your opponent (D/D Orthros) + a lot of resources/follow-up + Albion the Sanctifire Dragon + Berfomet the Mythical King of Phantom Beasts + 1 hand-rip + monster negate (Swordknight in GY) + targeting protection (Cornfield Coatl in GY). 
  1. Normal summon Mirror Swordknight. 
  2. Activate Mirror Swordknight's effect to summon Big-Winged Berfomet from deck.
  3. On summon, Big-Winged Berfomet searches for Chimera Fusion and Gazelle the King of Mythical Claws. 
  4. Activate Chimera Fusion to fusion summon Chimera the King of Phantom Beasts using Big-Winged Berfomet + Gazelle the King of Mythical Claws. 
  5. CL1 Big-Winged Berfomet to summon from GY Mirror Swordknight, CL2 Gazelle the King of Mythical Claws to search from deck any Illusion monster, CL3 Chimera the King of Phantom Beasts to send a random card from opponent's hand to the GY in the End Phase. 
  6. Activate Chimera Fusion in the GY to add it to your hand. 
  7. Activate Chimera Fusion to fusion summon Berfomet the Mythical King of Phantom Beasts by fusing Chimera the King of Phantom Beasts + any Beast, Fiend or Illusion. 
  8. On summon, Berfomet the Mythical King of Phantom Beasts sends to GY D/D Orthros (Or whatever target you'll summon with Sanctifire). 
  9. Activate Branded Fusion to fusion summon Albion The Sanctifire Dragon by sending Albaz + Light Spellcaster (usually Effect Veiler but it can also be Cartesia) from deck to GY. 
  10. During your end phase, resolve Chimera the King of Phantom Beasts' effect to send 1 random card for your opponent's hand to the GY. 
  11. During your opponent's draw phase, activate Sanctifire's effect to summon Big-Winged Berfomet to your field and D/D Orthros to your opponent's field. 
  12. CL1 (mandatory effect) D/D Orthros to lock your opponent out of special summoning anything except fiends, CL2 Big-Winged Berfomet to search for level 4 beast + Chimera Fusion to hand. 
This combo is particularly nasty since it is well protected and hard to interrupt with handtraps. Berfomet the Mythical King of Phantom Beasts makes fiend and beast floodgates very searchable, while Branded Fusion allows the deck to summon from GY a lingering floodgate to your opponent's field while summoning a resource generator to yours. Your opponent can't play while you amass resources for OTK next turn! 
 
The Chimera engine can search out Branded Fusion to start your Branded strategy! 
 
Mirror Swordknight = Search for Branded Fusion.
  1. Normal summon Mirror Swordknight. 
  2. Activate Mirror Swordknight's effect to summon Big-Winged Berfomet from deck.
  3. On summon, Big-Winged Berfomet searches for Chimera Fusion and Springans Kitt from deck. 
  4. Normal summon Springans Kitt. 
  5. Springans Kitt searches for Branded Fusion from deck. 
The Branded Engine can search for Mirror SwordKnight to initiate your Chimera strategy!
 
Branded Fusion = Search for Mirror Swordknight.
  1. Activate Branded Fusion, summoning Rindbrumm using Albaz + Gazelle the King of Mythical Claws. 
  2. Gazelle the King of Mythical Claw's effect activates when used as fusion material to search for any illusion monster. Add Cornfield Coatl from deck. 
  3. Discard Cornfield Coatl to add Mirror Swordknight from deck.
You can set up Dragoon before starting your entire Chimera combo to insulate your plays from handtraps or interruption!
 
Branded Fusion + Discard = Dragoon.
 
  1. Activate Branded Fusion, summoning Lubellion using Albaz + Versago the Destroyer.
  2. Activate Lubellion's summoning effect and discard 1 card to fusion summon Dragoon using Albaz and Versago in the GY. 
 
GENERAL TIPS
  • Branded Fusion makes greats Ash bait! For once, it's okay for Branded Fusion to get ash'd since your main strategy is with your Chimera cards! 
  • Dimensional Barrier and Simul Archfiends absolutely demolishes this deck. Oftentimes, the only counter to a blow-out like this is Triple Tactics Thrust so you can set a card to skip your opponent's turn in retaliation. 
  • Chimera Fusion can help your on-field monsters dodge targeting interruption like Imperm and Effect Veiler. Keep this in mind when activating effects! 
  • Summon your Illusion monsters in defense position. Since they all have the effect "cannot be destroyed by battle" except Diabellze, they form a robust defensive wall, especially against Tenpai. 
  • Droll and Lockbird usually stops this strategy since it needs multiple searches per turn. Shifter also severely limits what the deck can do as well.  
  • This deck can comfortably play the powerful infamous floodgate "There Can Be Only One." When going first vs. a deck susceptible to it, side them in! 
  • Other floodgate targets for you to summon with Chimera Branded are: Barrier Statue of the Abyss (Dark Attribute lock), Chaos Hunter (Anti-Banish floodgate), and Koa'ki Meiru Doom (Anti-Light/Dark effects). If you're playing for time, you can summon Red Resonator to gain lifepoints. 
  • A gimmicky (since it isn't searchable) but powerful combo is available with Fusion Armament. Activate Armament revealing Naturia Exterio to special summon Naturia Beast (although its negated) from the Extra Deck. Go through your Chimera combo sending Farfa, Malebranche of the Burning Abyss to the GY to banish Naturia Beast until the End Phase. When it comes back during your End Phase, it won't be negated anymore!
  • If you have Crossout Designator and you're summoning Berfomet the Mythical King of Phantom Beasts, you can easily summon any Fiend or Beast floodgate from deck. Activate Crossout, banishing your Fiend/Beast floodgate of choice. Go through Chimera combo and eventually send Berfomet the Mythical King of Phantom Beasts to the GY. During your opponent's turn, banish Berfomet to summon your floodgate from the banished pile! 
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
Yugi's Chimera deck has reached new powerlevels thanks to the modern retrain of Apprentice Illusion Magician - Nightmare Apprentice! Diabellze serving as the flagship floodgate for Chimera seems kind of ironic and funny, since she's used in Chimera more so than in her own archetype. As a "Yugi-Boomer" myself, I take great pride and joy playing oldschool retrains of cards hearkening back to early 2000s Yugioh - and the Chimera cards are exactly that! 
 
GLHF Duelists!

deck_description: Ahah big dinos... AND NOW WITH MEGAZORDS

I decided to revise one of my favorite decks and see what kind of silly tech I could incorporate this time.

Please note that this probably isn't even the most viable strategy (I think P.U.N.K. Ursartic is probably better if you seriously want to play this deck), but I'll see what I can do to improve it.

Your main lines involve getting to Ursarctic Polari (or Ursarctic Polar Star and Ursarctic Big Dipper at the same time, which is far better) to go into either the Ursarctic Synchro Monsters or a Level 9 (like Shenshen).You can also go into P.U.N.K. plays to access Adamancipator Risen - Dragite or even go for a play with Ultimaya Tzolkin to go into Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon (if you have any Spells or Traps).

The main little gimmicks I've included here are the small Ice Barrier engine with Lancea, which is coming out in Battles of Legend: Terminal Revenge this June, and Ocean Dragon Lord - Kairyu-Shin. The former provides great disruption once it's destroyed by going into Trishula, Zero Dragon of the Ice Barrier (which in turn can go into Trishula, Dragon of the Ice Barrier) and floodgates in the form of General Raiho of the Ice Barrier and Medium of the Ice Barrier.The latter is a floodgate searchable with Atlantean Dragoons, which is really good in this format. I will say it's much harder to bring it out without Icejade Tremora, and you can replace it with any other Sea Serpent monster that might be better here (not that I know of any...).

That's all! Have fun!

deck_excerpt: Some say the price of holding heat is often too high- you either be in the coffin or you be the new guy.
deck_description:
A prototype Machina Horus SHS deck that abuses the high number of one-card starters and discard potential to create a pile of cards that gains some new tech every time you look at it. From being able to summon Gearframe off Regulus or Giantrainer pairing perfectly with a heavy-monster SHS strategy, this deck is capable of some truly terrible things. The side and extra are works in progress based on cards I already own so I know they can be improved, but the main deck is plenty potent and really only needs ratio revisions to personal taste. I could see going up one Regulus, but there's enough lines into it to not be an issue.

This would probably be meta if not for its weakness to certain hand traps that are prevalent thanks to Snake Eyes- an unanswered Dimension Shifter is a lot harder to get out of even with the variety of starters you have access to. Since you can't easily answer it without spells, a few made it into the sideboard. It might be worth risking the SHS package going offline, but it's so hand-dependant that I wouldn't risk running more than you absolutely need. Experiment and see what feels right.

Notes:
-I tried other engines other engines like Horus or Kashtira, so far this is really good.

-Deck is having trouble with negating the search and if you don't have a follow-up, you can't establish a board.

-The new Salamangreat needs more experimentation and I am sure there are a good version out there other than this or Kashtira.

deck_description:
It's Salamangreat. You have 12 1 card combos (1.5 with cynet mining). Everything revolves around Stallio for the good endboards. Promethean Princess does a lot of heavy lifting as a fire version of Transcode Talker AND she's a disrupt. The 1 card ends on 1 trap + Prom + relinked Raging Phoenix. The old Spinny + Gazelle ends on the same thing, but with both traps. There are a few combos that let you play through Nibiru, revolving around Weasel and Gazelle ( ie make Stallio without burning your normal, but Nibiru is a problem for this deck that must be respected).  

Regular Phoenix is an alternative to Raging, so you can nuke your opponent's board. You can run Code of Soul as a means to set up a quick effect board nuke, but that is already covered by Rage and 3 handtraps is generally better than the Code of Soul engine. 

Handtraps and Side Deck choices is whatever is relevant. Think of it as having 18 free  slots in main and 15 free slots in side for a total of *checks calculator* 33 free slots. The better part is that this can go first and second. *glares at Tenpai*
