deck_excerpt: Earth Machine is back and has been given a serious overhaul. This is my most recent build I've used to reach Platinum several times in a row
deck_description:
This is my most recent upgrade to my beloved Earth Machine Trains deck. For about 3 or 4 months in a row I reached Platinum and almost hit Diamond consistently with this build of Trains. The deck has changed significantly but the core concepts remain somewhat the same. 

OVERVIEW: Earth Machine is an aggressive pressure oriented deck that aims to use powerful high octane Earth Machine monsters like Number 81: Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Super Dora , Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Juggernaut Liebe , Machina Citadel and Therion "King" Regulus to control various aspects of the duel. Your main tactic is to rely on sheer brute force and utilize various Quick Effects to disrupt your opponent. The goal overall is to constantly acquire resources to dump down threat after threat each and every turn until you eventually smash through your opponent's defenses and win the duel.

GOING FIRST: Going first, you generally want to build up an end board consisting of Number 81: Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Super Dora and Therion "King" Regulus. You should always prioritize summong Number 81: Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Super Dora and if you get a clunky or unoptimal opening hand, it's much safer to end your turn with a defense position Number 81.

What I love about Number 81 is that it can, at spell speed 2, make itself immune to all card effects, and having the ultimate Towers with 4k defense gives you a powerful wall. However, we can further abuse this quick effect in combination with Heavy Freight Train Derricrane, which upon being detached from an Xyz monster, allows you to destroy any card on the field. This is your main form of disruption.

Your second best form of disruption comes in the form of Therion "King" Regulus! Because after so many years, Earth Machine finally has an omni negate! If you've already comfortably summoned Number 81 and have the means to extend into another search, you'll be searching for Regulus to give you another point of disruption. 

The third piece to our trifecta of awesomeness is Machina Citadel! Which you can easily summon with the trap card Machina Overdrive! The downside of Overdrive can easily be avoided thanks to Number 81's ability to become immune to everything. The ideal strategy is chain 1, use Overdrive, then chain 2, use Number 81. So now, Number 81 won't be destroyed by Overdrive, but you'll also get to special summon Citadel from the deck! What makes Citadel so good and worth summoning? His ability is a spell speed 2 Raigeki! And we can yet again use Number 81's immunity to our favor. Activate Citadel, target Number 81, and then watch the magic! Now all monsters your opponent controls with 3200 or less attack are nuked and you've got 2 terrifying boss monsters still on the field.

By the way, you can also search Machina Overdrive with Machina Redeployment. 

Another awesome monster you can combo into and act as another piece of disruption is Infinitrack River Stormer, specifically, River Stormer with Infinitrack Road Roller attached to it as material. This is a very annoying floodgate that puts all your opponent's monsters in DEF mode, making it even harder for your opponent to fight back against your powerful trains. 

GOING SECOND: If you win the coin toss, you should always choose to go first. Because your going first boss monsters are much more valuable, much safer and more resilient than going second. However, what makes Earth Machine so dangerous is that although it prefers to go first, it has no problem going second as you can easily setup an OTK on your first turn going second! 

Under normal circumstances, you will usually want to setup an OTK by first summoning Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Gustav Max, which can burn your opponent for 2000, then rank it up into my favorite card: Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Juggernaut Liebe! Who can boost itself up to 6000 attack points. And 2000+6000 = Checkmate! 

To prevent any kind of disruption, (and believe me, they're gonna have something) be it a sneaky trap card or your opponent's own boss monster. We'll again be using Heavy Freight Train Derricrane. When you detach Derricrane from Gustav, you can pop any card in play. Which further allows us to push forward into our glorious Juggernaut OTK.

As I previously stated, if given the choice, choose to go first. Because we can always just go for the Juggernaut OTK on our second turn, and it's much easier to do after the first few turns of the game. 

COMBOS: Oh gosh, there's so much to explain here. As the combos of this deck are not as concrete or easy as they used to be. As I stated in the Overview, your main strategy is to continuously acrue resources and apply constant pressure. It's a unique Beatdown / Midrange hybrid that can only be properly understood after you've played with this deck yourself. 

Your main turn 1 combo is to do 2 things with your opening combo: the first is of course, to summon Number 81: Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Super Dora , but the second mandatory thing you'll want to do is Draw 2 cards with Infinitrack Tunneller. We all know how powerful Pot of Greed is, so the question now becomes, how do we turn our Tunneller into pot of greed?
By dumping dozens of Extra Deck monsters into the GY of course! This is why we play so many dinky Xyz & Link Monsters like Infinitrack Goliath, Ancient Gear Ballista and Gear Gigant X. In the following paragraphs, I'll go over the most common openers and combos to allow us to both draw 2 cards and summon the big bad Number 81: Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Super Dora 

Combo #1: Machina Gearframe Combo  (requires Machina Gearframe & any Level 10 Machine in hand)
Normal Summon Machina Gearframe ; add Machina Unclaspare to your hand. This will Special Summon Unclaspare. Activate Unclaspare's effect and send Machina Fortress to your GY. Then Xyz Summon Gear Gigant X. Using Gigant X's ability. We will search for Infinitrack Harvester
(note, if Harvester is already in your opening hand, you will search for Flying Pegasus Railroad Stampede )
Then, discard your Level 10 Machine to Special Summon Machina Fortress. Now use both Fortress and Gear Gigant X as link material to Link Summon Platinum Gadget. We will then use Platinum Gadget's ability to Special Summon Infinitrack Harvester.
Harvester will then search out Infinitrack Brutal Dozer. Now, use Harvester as material to Link Summon Infinitrack Goliath. Now tribute Goliath to Special Summon Brutal Dozer. Dozer will special summon Infinitrack Tunneller. Now use both Tunneller and Brutal Dozer to Xyz summon Infinitrack River Stormer! Detach Tunneller from River Stormer to search for Heavy Freight Train Derricrane. Now, we'll use River Stormer as material to link summon another Infinitrack Goliath. Summoning Goliath will let us Special Summon Derricrane. Now, tribute Platinum Gadget to Special Summon River Stormer from the GY.  Now send both Goliath and River Stormer to the GY to Link Summon Double Headed Anger Knuckle, who we will then use to Sac Itself to special summon the level 10 machine we discarded. Now, we can activate Tunneller, putting the 5 extra deck monsters in your GY back into your Extra Deck and drawing 2 cards! So you now have 2 Level 10 machines to summon Number 81 and a fresh hand full of gas! 

Combo #2: Infinitrack Harvester Combo  (requires Infinitrack Harvester and a Train in hand)
Normal Summon Infinitrack Harvester ; add Infinitrack Brutal Dozer to your hand. Now use Harvester as Link Material to summon Infinitrack Goliath. Now tribute Goliath to Special Summon Brutal Dozer. Dozer will special summon Infinitrack Tunneller. Make our beloved Infinitrack River Stormer, then special summon the Train in your hand. Detach Tunneller to add a different Train to your hand. Use River Stormer as Link Material to go into another Goliath. Then sacrifice Goliath to revive River Stormer, then Special Summon the second Train from your hand, then sac River Stormer again for the 3rd Goliath. Now use Goliath and 1 of your 2 trains to go into Double Headed Anger Knuckle. Now tribute Knuckle to special summon the Level 10 train you just put into your GY. And once again, you now have 5 Extra Deck monsters in your GY and 2 Level 10 Trains in play. 

Combo #3: Infinitrack Harvester Solo Combo  (Only requires Infinitrack Harvester in hand, but doesn't end with Number 81)
Normal Summon Infinitrack Harvester, add Infinitrack Brutal Dozer to your hand. Use Infinitrack Harvester as Link Material to summon Infinitrack Goliath. Then tribute Goliath to special summon Brutal Dozer. Brutal Dozer this time will summon Infinitrack Road Roller. Now use Brutal Dozer as Link Material to link summon another Infinitrack Goliath. Then, use Road Roller as Link Material to link summon the 3rd copy of Infinitrack Goliath. Now use both of your Infinitrack Goliaths to link summon Ancient Gear Ballista. Ballista will add Ancient Gear Box to your hand, and when Gear Box is added to your hand, you can then add Infinitrack Tunneller to your hand. Tribute Ancient Gear Ballista to special summon Tunneller. This will trigger the effect of Infinitrack Road Roller and it will summon itself to your field. Now you can Xyz summon Infinitrack Harvester and use it's ability to add Therion "King" Regulus to your hand (detach Tunneller). Now Special Summon Regulus and equip it with Brutal Dozer. Now use Tunneller to shuffle Harvester back to your main deck, and put the 4 Link Monsters back into your Extra Deck. And your end board will be a Harvester+Road Roller and your Omni Negate. Pay attention to this combo in particular, because when Konami prints new, much better Earth Machine Link Monsters, this specific combo will get way, way, way, WAY stronger.

Combo #4: Machina Metalcruncher Combo (Requires Machina Metalcruncher and 1 Train OR Brutal Dozer)
Normal Summon Machina Metalcruncher, show your opponent 3 copies of either Heavy Freight Train Derricrane OR 3 copies of Infinitrack Brutal Dozer (depends what's in your hand). Tribute Metalcruncher to Special Summon Brutal Dozer, then special summon Infinitrack Road Roller  from the deck, and Special Summon the Train from your hand. Send Brutal Dozer to the GY as Link Material to summon Infinitrack Goliath. Now send Road Roller to the GY as Link Material to summon another copy of Infinitrack Goliath. Now with your 2 Goliaths, use them to link summon Ancient Gear Ballista, which will add Ancient Gear Box, and adding Box to your hand allows you to also add Infinitrack Tunneller to your hand! Now tribute Ancient Gear Ballista to summon Tunneller. This will trigger Road Roller to summon itself from your GY. Now with Tunneller and Road Roller, make the Xyz monster; Infinitrack Harvester. Detach Tunneller to add a different train to your hand. Now use River Stormer as Link Material to summon your 3rd Infinitrack Goliath. This will allow you to special summon the Train from your hand. Now use that train and Goliath as material to Link Summon: Double Headed Anger Knuckle. You will then sac Anger Knuckle to special summon the Train you just put in your GY. Now you yet again have 2 Level 10's that will let you summon Number 81: Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Super Dora and you can put 5 Extra Deck monsters back into deck to draw 2 cards. 

CONCLUSION: This build of Trains is much stronger than older versions I've posted on this website. This one has much greater variety, and there's so many more flashy and insane combos you can pull off once you fully get the hang of the deck. Its one of the many reasons I love this deck, there's just so much stuff you can do. Its awesome! <3 However, no deck is perfect. And this deck definitely has many weaknesses, the biggest one is not being able to fit enough hand traps into the main deck. But I've put a bunch of other recommendations in the Side Deck that you can add to your own build of Trains. The cards listed in the Side Deck can help fix the weaknesses this deck has. 

Your biggest weakness is Maxx "C". Maxx C is an infuriating card to play through. So if you can, try to find as many was as possible to hard counter Maxx C. Crossout Designator and/or extra copies of Called by the Grave and Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring help very much. 

Extra copies of Forbidden Droplet are excellent because you can use Ancient Gear Box as the perfect fodder to discard with Droplet. 

Cosmic Cyclone and Lightning Storm acts as additional copies of Backrow removal. Backrow decks like Eldlich and Labrynth are without question, Trains' worst matchup. 

Book of Moon & Gameciel, the Sea Turtle Kaiju act as the perfect answer to deal with gigantic threats that dare try to grow bigger than Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Juggernaut Liebe. 

Tinker with some of the weak points and find what works for you. This is just the version of Earth Machine Trains that I find to be the best to play for my specific playstyle. 

Good Luck and Have Fun obliterating your enemies with gigantic trains!

deck_excerpt: The Horus cards have finally reached Masterduel! Time to slot them in the strongest and most abusable decks possible!
deck_description:
The Horus cards have finally reached Masterduel with the "Revived Legion" selection pack! A ton of decks just have been made viable and recieved buffs due to these cards, and that includes the Bystial archetype.

It turns out that slapping together beatstick handtraps (Bystials), level 8 extenders (Horus) and a tuner package (Resonators) is enough to power through the brutal Masterduel ladder! Functioning as a midrange-aggro deck with a robust resource grindgame, Horus Bystial kind of reminds me of Dragonlink except with more Synchro boss monsters and less combo steps! This mid-range, staple oriented playstyle is certainly fun to play! It reminds me of playing PUNK or Live Twin, but this time with eldritch dragons and Egyptian themed guardians!

If you want a thorough guide on how to play this deck, check out my article from last year.

Here are some key characteristics of a Deck O'Fun:

  1. Creative Themes: Deck O'Fun decks often center around creative themes or concepts that may not be optimized for competitive play but are entertaining nonetheless. These themes could be based on anything from pop culture references to obscure card interactions.

  2. Unconventional Strategies: Rather than focusing solely on winning, Deck O'Fun decks may prioritize fun and variety. They might feature unconventional strategies or combos that aim to surprise or amuse both players.

  3. Casual Gameplay: Deck O'Fun decks are typically designed for casual, friendly matches rather than high-stakes tournaments. They encourage experimentation and creativity without the pressure of competitive play.

  4. Inclusion of Favorite Cards: Players often include their favorite cards, even if they're not the most powerful or efficient options. This personal touch adds to the enjoyment of playing with a Deck O'Fun.

  5. Balanced Power Level: While some Deck O'Fun decks may include powerful cards or strategies, they're generally balanced to ensure a fun and engaging experience for both players. This means avoiding overly oppressive strategies or lock-out combos that can lead to one-sided matches.

Overall, the primary objective of a Deck O'Fun is to promote enjoyment, creativity, and interaction between players. It's a great way to relax, have fun with friends, and explore the vast possibilities of the Yu-Gi-Oh! trading card game beyond the realm of competitive play.

deck_excerpt: Surprise your opponent and go first as tenpai
deck_description:
If anyone remembers the Mathmech/evil-eye play, this is essentially the same thing but with tenpai/kash. The gameplan is to want to go second in round 1 using tenpai to break boards, throw out hand traps, and OTK. Your opponent will think you are playing tenpai so they will opt for you to go first. This is where you sided out all your tenpai/sangen AND lightning storms for your full kashtira engine. 

These decks work great because of the overlap of some engine/non-engine cards like terraforming, fenrir, D-shifter (crazy). Meaning you can bait out interaction with pressured planet because your opponent wont know if you are getting a unicorn or a fenrir. 

Pot of prosperity is insanely easy to use. Just banish the 6 cards of the engine you arent using.

If there are other decks that can do the same thing with tenpai lemme know Im trying to think of some.

deck_excerpt: Branded Despia with a bit of spice(not rly)
deck_description:
Braded Despia decklist with some minor adjusments 

3x Sky striker multirole is there to protect mainly your Branded Fusion but it comes in handy with other stuff too

1x Quem becouse it's searchable through Opening and mostly feels really bad to draw her,since you would mainly prefer to start with Aluber

Dramaturge bcs noone ever expects it :)

I cut out few of the main deck Abions,simply bcs even tho High Spirits line is really good,it way too greedy,and you already play a decent amount of dragon monsters

Extra deck is pretty much standard

As for the side:

2x Kurikara to break the stationary boards such as manadium,and its really good into the snake eyes matchup

Shaddoll Dragon agains floodgate heavy decks and backrow,you can just send it off of Branded Fusion

Bunch of backrow hate,cut that's what kills this deck

Droll bcs u kinda have to,lots of deck that just loose to droll this format and also most decks that this deck has bad matchup against looses to droll

And one of each "Floodgate traps" simpy bcs they are searchable from TT Thrust,so you techinaclly play 4 of each 

As for the reasons:

D Barrier-lots of Synchro and Fusion decks loose to it immidietly

Simul Archfiend-Tenpai matchup bcs they can do Princess raging Phineix OTK through D Barrier

DD Grounds Snake Eyes just Diest from it same as Evenly if they dont make S:P

Placement: Top 16

Deck Description: Chaos Ruler - A Blend of Power and Control

This Yu-Gi-Oh! deck revolves around a unique blend of powerful monsters and strategic control elements. Here's a breakdown of its core functionalities:

  • The Chaos Core: The deck utilizes "Chaos" monsters like "The Chaos Creator" and "Chaos Witch" alongside their support cards like "Shell of Chaos" and "Core of Chaos." This engine allows for searching and special summoning, facilitating explosive combos and access to strong monsters.
  • Bystial Legion: The deck incorporates the "Bystial" archetype with monsters like "Bystial Druiswurm" and "Bystial Magnamhut." These provide a strong search and removal engine, disrupting your opponent's plays while setting up your own.
  • Control Elements: Hand traps like "Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring" and "Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit" help disrupt your opponent's key plays. Additionally, powerful traps like "Solemn Judgment" and "Called by the Grave" offer protection and negation against threats.
  • Versatile Options: Cards like "Necroface" and "Branded Regained" provide graveyard manipulation, fueling combos and reviving powerful monsters. "Allure of Darkness" helps filter your deck and potentially discard combo pieces.
  • Fusion Power: With cards like "Gold Sarcophagus" and "Foolish Burial," the deck can access powerful Fusion monsters like "Elder Entity N'tss" and "Ultimaya Tzolkin" for game-ending plays.
  • Extra Deck Toolbox: The Extra Deck offers diverse options for various situations. "Chaos Angel" can be summoned with ease thanks to the "Chaos" monsters, "Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon" offers negation, and "PSY-Framelord Omega" provides powerful resource advantage.

Overall Playstyle: This deck aims to establish a strong board presence with powerful "Chaos" or "Bystial" monsters while maintaining control of the duel through hand traps and powerful traps. It can also delve into Fusion Summons for devastating effects.

Weaknesses: The deck relies on specific card combinations to pull off its strongest plays. Consistency can be an issue if you don't draw the necessary pieces. Additionally, some hand traps may not be effective against all strategies.

 

Who should play this deck? This deck is ideal for players who enjoy a blend of combo and control, utilizing powerful monsters while strategically disrupting their opponent's plays. It offers a complex and rewarding playstyle, but may require practice to master.

deck_excerpt: Lair of Darkness tag teams with Fang of Critias fusions and Zeus (because why not)
deck_description:
PLEASE READ:

Basically a Lair of Darkness tribute spam with Ladys of lamet, searching either Crush Card or Mirror Force for Critias fusions, also optional Mask Change II for gy and hand control if you are struggling with floating effects.

many optional hand traps as well as Acquisitivness incase you're playing against a banishing opsessed opponent (eg Orcust)

anything is swapable for anything you want to add (hence Mask Change engine in the side deck) like handtraps in side if you need and many possible engines (these are just my personal favourites on the list).

Pot of Prosperity is not required but helps a tone when searching for literally anything you need, run as many as possible if you have the funds but is not required for the base engines to function, just seriously helps with unbricking etc.

Extra Deck is generic links and Beat cop for lair protection, Zeus Package with Gossip Shadow and D/D/D Darius, Dark Law, Critias fusions.

 

Optional engines:

  • Bystial
  • Super-poly for muddragon or starving vemon
  • Malicious + armageddon knight + foolish
  • Critias engine
  • Zeus package
  • Orcust if you really want to...

...

should be legal, hopefully...

but will update if not

The side deck is full with some cards that you can exchange with main or extra deck cards. you can also increas the nubers of runick spell cards according to how you fell with the ratio. I also think i have too much free spot, at least 1 more keaf would be great but idk 

for extra i choose cupid over coral because it is easier to summon, let you the acces to hugin and give mor flexibility for synchro. but coral is also great because you can summon it under ice barrier effect

deck_name: Top 8 Italian Open 2024 Rome - Branded Despia
deck_excerpt: Branded Despia Fusion Albaz Droplet Talent Thrust
deck_description: Top 8 Italian Open 2024 Rome - Branded Despia pile with 53 main deck cards

In most cases, still damage reflection hard counters most strategies in the higher ranks, especially the pesky tier 1 fire decks in Masterduel! Your Mikanko monsters are summoned untargetable and indestructible due to the mechanics/nature of the deck, immediately rendering many interactions of the Snake-Eye cards useless!

CHEESE out wins consistently towards opponents who are consistently not ready to face kaijus, boardbreakers and untargetable, indestructible, battle-immune shrine maidens! Not only are these ladies beautiful, they're terrifyingly potent and they interact with opponent's boards in ways that most decks aren't ready for!

The May version of Mikanko has taken a slight hit to consistency with Nadir Servant going from 3 -> 2. The Main deck has one new Mikanko support card, Mikanko Spiritwalk which is a powerful trap card that removes an opponent's monster as well as gives you follow-up for following turns with it's monster reborn effect. Other than that, Mikanko OTK still is more or less the same deck with identical strategy.

Check out my previous written guide on this deck from last year!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

deck_excerpt: Save the day with some old schooling
deck_description: A mix of everything interesting about the HERO archetype with some agressive retorts.

Budget battle phase. Dimension Shifter works fine here. You can still swing for game under that. You don't need Heat Wave but it can be helpful if your in a match setting with being forced into going first round 2/3. However, the Black Wing Assault burn and Hieratic spin are nice. Plus you should side in 3 Crossout/1 Dimensional Barrier for extra precaution. Depending on what your up against, Necrovalley can really swing the game in your favor. Trident Dragion, Raging Phoenix, and Little Knight are great but way too expensive right now. (At the time of writing this, Dragion is ~$100, Raging ~$50, and Little Knight ~$120). Just don't run Pot of Prosperity and you will still OTK even after using Upstart Goblin. Maybe tech in Pot of Desires if your feeling lucky. Dimensional barrier sucks to play in to. You're still able to get Zealantis out without Phoenix either way, just not as powerful of an end board. Still pretty threatening. Zealantis wins games by himself.

deck_name: Branded Tearlament Kashtira Horus Bystial Snake-Eye Dogmatika (Limit 1 Festival) (May 2024)
deck_excerpt: I "overcooked" for Masterduel's Limit 1 Festival... 60 card giga pile is surprisingly consistent and powerful!
deck_description:
I "overcooked" for Masterduel's Limit 1 Festival... I literally just jammed every engine and powerful fusion deck together to form this monstrosity... And it's surprisingly powerful, consistent and can play through all interruptions! IT JUST WORKS!!!

There is no guide, article or step-by-step combo to this deck - just play with whatever cards you draw! Just some tips - 2 monsters = Anaconda -> Branded Fusion. Small World can literally search every starter. Grass Grows Greener is an insta-win card.

Overall, this "Limit 1 Festival" was the most fun I've had in Masterduel in a while! Every duel feels fresh and exciting, and drawing 1-ofs tickles the dopamine part of my gambling brain to no end!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

deck_excerpt: If you can only run 1 card each, just run 4 main deck engines!
deck_description:
For the Limit 1 Festival, I've decided to play something slightly silly. I didn't want to just run a version of a deck I like, but now it sucks in the grind and is inconsistent. So I instead used a brand new toy I've grown fond of with some old engines I like. Presenting: Adventure Bystial Dogmatika Horus!

The basic game-plan is to just get into something. For Adventure, Rite/Enchantress is a 1 card combo into an omni. For Bystial, there's no outright 1 card combo but opening any Bystial is disruptio against the common Branded Tearlaments decks I've seen in the event. For Dogmatika, Ecclesia searches out Punishment, Fleurdelis, or allows you to do the Matrix into Alba Zoa line if your opponent has a monster on the field. For Horus, we run an effective 3 copies of King's Sarc, with Canopic acting as a 4th backup method to get Horus monsters onto the field.

Each of these engines are good at both forcing a grind game and winning in simplified game states. King's Sarcophagus represents a massive supply of bodies that can turn themselves into useful XYZ or Link monsters, in addition to being huge and having useful effects if your opponent gets any funny ideas, for example.

The Extra deck is a mish-mash of Rank 8s, Synchros to make using our level 4 tuners, Dogmatika Punishment targets, and a couple useful Links to fill things out. It's pretty flexible, our ED is not an especially strong focus here. Feel free to experiment.

deck_excerpt: I have become a meta sheep.

deck_description:
The deck I used for the Limit 1 Event.

The deck got me just above 90% win rate only losing to stun decks and some of the loner Kash ~ It has great versatility and can always seem to end on endboards you would with the normal deck quite easily. It can defo brick but usually, there is at least 1 card to get the Darklord despian ball rolling. You could of course add the real albaz/mirrorjade branded package to this but I have come to loath it and prefer to stick the edgy boys. 

There is room for improvement but this is just what I ended the event on.
Salad

Skeleton for an Atlantean / Mermail / Deep Sea deck, with Diva being a central piece and Minstrel a hell of a card. The deck focuses on swarming to convert into synchros and discarding to trigger effects.

Alternatives choices include Tidal fresh off the banlist (at time of writing), Poseidra because it has nice art, Abyssleed is a chonky boi, Lappis Dragon can be summoned if added of Bahamut for extension, Abyssturge a recovery option, Sea Nettle is an extender, Abyssnerei can pop Abysslinde to trigger both of their effects but it ain't too hot, Abysshilde is neat utility but you tend to discard stuff, and then extra deck and S/T choices.

Haven't tested enough.

deck_excerpt: I mean, most of the tear cards are on the F/L list anyway
deck_description:
A tearlaments deck for the Master Duel Limit 1 festival, may 2024. This deck has a bunch of synergistic engines between tearlaments, horus, and kashtira, so you can flex into whichever engine you want based on your opening hand, though the strongest one is usually tearlaments. I've been using board breakers more than hand traps in the festival because Snake Eyes are really popular and 1 hand trap doesn't do anything to that strategy really. This deck is pretty consistent and has a bunch of searchers and mill, but it sometimes struggles playing into an established board.

Still, if you're looking for something to play that isn't Snake-Eyes, I think Tear is a pretty decent option.
